The road to the double helix, the structure of DNA.
Fifty years earlier, on 25 April 1953, James Watson and Francis Crick published a short letter in the scientific journal
The second major advance took place a few months later, when Max Perutz discovered a technique aimed toward determining the structures of large molecules like myoglobin and hemoglobin.
Since then, structural analysis by radiographic protein molecules has enabled us to understand the chemistry of biological reactions.
Both discoveries (the structures of DNA and proteins) were discovered in the Cavendish laboratory of the University of Cambridge.
So why these two memorial stones of the revolution of biology and medicine that have dominated science in the second half of the 20
The major breakthroughs in 1953, were based on experimental physics such as it has been practiced at Cambridge since the end of the 19th century.
That legacy has shaped the intellectual environment in which was formed the father-son team composed of William and Lawrence Bragg and in which Lawrence Bragg, first as a student then as a student researcher, developed in 1912 the ideas that lead to structural analysis by radiography.
Although Max von Laue, Walter Friedrich and Paul Knipping have discovered the diffraction of X-rays by crystals, it was Lawrence Bragg who discovered a way to exploit scientifically this discovery.
Reflection by "Bragg planes," the sheets of atoms capable of diffracting X-rays in specific ways based on the separation between the sheets, led Bragg to calculate the exact arrangement of sodium and chloride atoms in a grain of salt.
William Bragg earned a degree in mathematics at Cambridge in 1884 and became a professor of physics at Adelaide in Australia.
In 1909, he returned to England to occupy a chair in Leeds, while continuing his work on the nature of X-rays.
He became the director of the Royal Institution in London in 1923, where he drew the attention of some exceptional young scientists, interested in X-rays.
Among them were two new graduates in Cambridge, William Astbury and John Desmond Bernal, who became interested in the problem of the protein structure, Astbury following a request to Bragg, provided X-ray patterns of wool and silk.
Bernal came back to Cambridge as a structural crystallography professor in 1927 and was promoted as assistant director of research in crystallography in 1923, at this time a sub-department of Cavendish Laboratory.
Bernal was interested first in the atomic structure of cristals, metals and minerals, then in hormones and sterols, and certain amino acids, the components of protein.
Meanwhile, Astbury 'set up in Leeds in 1928, where he also began to work on the amino acids and proteins.
While describing his fruitless attempts to obtain well-ordered patterns of radiographic diffraction from the crystals of the pepsin protein, he wondered if Bernal could help him get crystals of other proteins.
A friend of Bernal, Glenn Millikan, came to visit a laboratory in Uppsala, Sweden, where researchers had managed to obtain large crystals of pepsin, some of which were recorded to be always in their mother liquor, Cambridge.
Bernal and Dorothy Crowfoot (Hodgkin after her marriage) obtained patterns of dry crystals, just as Astbury did, with equally disappointing results.
But when Bernal observed the crystals under a light microscope, he noted that when the significant amount of water contained in the crystal network evaporated, the crystal's order disrupted because of it.
They repeated the experience with X-rays, but with the crystal surrounded by its mother liquor and sealed in a glass capillary, in this way obtaining patterns including several crystal reflections.
The results of the first defining moment in protein crystallography were published in the form of a letter in the magazine
Max Perutz, having gotten a degree in chemistry in Vienna, joined Cambridge in 1935 to work as a graduate student with Bernal.
The following year, he received excellent haemoglobin crystals and soon produced the best standards of X-ray diffraction to date.
But the observable diagram of diffraction (intensities and positions of the individual reflexions) represents only half of the necessary data to deduce the structure of object of diffraction.
In terms of mathematics, this plan gives the magnitude, but not the stages (i.e., the stages of a oscillatory movement) without which it is impossible to determine the atomic positions.
With more simple structures composed of a lower number of atoms, chemistry, could provide important information about atomic tendencies and a solution could be found by trial and error.
But the proteins, which contain thousands of atoms, were far too complicated for this solution to work.
Thus, in spite of the impressive quantity of excellent data collected, the solution remained cruelly out of reach.
But the faith in obtaining detailed information on the protein structure from X-ray patterns remained, but only if these data could be discovered.
It was to be expected that where chemistry had failed, physics and their first laboratory showed the way, a way taken by Watson and Crick in the epic breakthrough that we celebrate this month.
Separate worlds
Macroeconomic policies,financial globalisation and changes in labour market institutions have exacerbated inequalities in recent years. These include not only levels of income and wealth, but also access to education, health, welfare as well as political participation and influence.
Even in the countries with a fast economic growth, a set of factors, exacerbated by demographic changes, has led to the transmission of gaps in knowledge, social responsibilities and opportunities from a generation to another.
A shown by the United Nations with the 2005 Report on the social situation in the world: the inequality crisis, few countries, rich or poor, have proved immune to the global rise in inequality or its impact on education, health and social well-being.
There is of course no relationship of simple cause and effect that links poverty and the inequality in violence.
But inequalities and a sense of deprivation contribute to resentment and social instability, and threaten security.
Excluded and having only somber future prospects, the young, in particular, often experience a certain anomie and take refuge in anti-social, and even violent, behavior.
Not more than a simple explanation about the causes of poverty exists.
It is clear, however, that poverty stems from different and complex conditions, and that improvement requires a multifaceted approach.
It is difficult to imagine how to, for example, "send poverty to the dustbin of history" (Make Poverty History) without generating enough work, educational opportunities and health for all.
It is certain that the world has witnessed some progress in several areas in recent decades.
Access to education for girls has improved and some differences due to the gap between the sexes have been reduced.
In spite of AIDS and the resurgence of malaria and tuberculosis, life expectancy has increased almost everywhere in the world thanks to the improvement of public health systems.
Overall, however, the gap of inequalities remains wide and in some cases it is even expanding.
The most important determinant of income inequality today is the inequality of wealth, with the increased concentration of ownership of assets in recent years as primary cause greater inequality of income in most countries.
While galloping unemployment, the qualifications gap and decreasing productivity, along with the "dé-formalization" and "dé-méthodology" that have impacted the job markets have exacerbated the inequality of incomes throughout the world, the number of "working poor" and the "growth in the number of unemployed" have increased.
Not more than the stabilization and structural adjustment programs, imposed since the 1980s, have really fulfilled their promises of higher economic growth.
Growth almost everywhere in the world over the past twenty-five years has been weaker than in the preceding 25 years, despite massive growth of East Asia, India and some other countries.
Such differences in growth suggests that worldwide inequalities on the whole may not have increased unequivocally.
But the inequalities nationally has escalated in most countries in the past years, largely because of economic liberalization, both nationally and internationally.
Indeed, in many parts of the world, this kind of economic reform has in fact undermined growth rates as well as the initiating role of governments, while increasing overall inequality in other respects.
The rare exceptions are usually due to the measured or persistent interventions of certain governments.
But these are exceptions: the cumulative impact of these reforms over the past 25 years has produced a greater inequality in most developed and developing countries with rising unemployment, greater income disparities, reduction of social protection and environmental degradation.
The liberalisation of the international financial sector, for example, has undermined the use of development grants that are more inclusive and better targeted to promote economic activities.
Furthermore, contrary to the promises of its supporters, financial liberalization has in fact resulted in net capital movements from those who had the least to those who had the most in the long term, while increasing financial volatility and weakening economic activity.
Meanwhile, negotiations on the liberalization of trade appeared to ignore the historical trends.
The conditions of international trade in developing countries have gone worse: the price of commodities have declined compared to the manufactured products, just as the price of tropical agricultural products compared with prices of agricultural products from tempered countries, and the prices of generic products fell as a result of a production protected by laws on intellectual property.
Consequently, the trade liberalisation of manufactured products led to shrinking industry and a strong increase in unemployment in most parts of the world as in the case of textiles this past year.
And, while the liberalisation of agricultural trade could improve the export income of some poor countries, the main beneficiaries will be none other than the richest agricultural exporters.
The countries which import the currently subsidized products will suffer.
"The disengagement from the State" which has occurred recently in a large part of the developed world has generally involved a reduced role for the State, particularly in its ability to initiate and support development as well as in its social interventions in the areas of public education, health, housing and public services.
The economic liberalisation put in place in many countries in the past 25 years was, from the beginning, a questionable policy and its consequences have become completely obvious.
If the world does not focus on finding the appropriate economic policies, that will address the negative impact of economic inequalities on reducing the growth and poverty, poor and privileged people will continue to live in separate worlds.
One should not follow the Federal Reserve
The Federal Reserve of the United States Etats-unis faces a dilemna, because it must continue to raise its rates despite an economy devastated by Hurricane Katrina.
The inability of the Reserve to raise rates sooner teaches the European Central Bank a lesson: after a prolonged period of monetary stability with unusually low interest rates, waiting too long to raise rates to more normal and appropriate levels can have dangerous consequences.
The reserve took its time starting the process of rate normalisation and it is now paying the price.
The ECB should not make the same mistake, even if we consider that these two central banks operate under different backgrounds and under constraints.
The warning signs of impending inflation abound in all of the Eurozone.
The growth in money supply is well above target levels for some time, indicating excessive liquidity.
Headline inflation in September, to 2.6%, is superior to the target of 2% of the ECB, as is the latest forecasts for inflation in 2006 (updated forecasts come in early December).
"The period of wage restraint may be coming to an end," we were warned by Otmar Issing, the head of the ECB, implying that soaring energy prices may have risen now along with the general price level (also called secondary effects).
In these circumstances, there is no good reason to wait any longer before raising interest rates.
The longer energy prices remain at today's high levels, the greater the likelihood that anticipation of inflation will rise and the side-effects will begin to materialize.
Further procrastination on the normalisation of leading interest rates from the ECB could well lead to a nasty bout of inflation.
It would be catastrophic for Europe and the economic recovery since the ECB would have no choice but to slam on the monetary brakes.
No one really wants this.
Better an increase on the base of 50 points now, thus allowing the economic recovery to continue in curbing inflation, than an increase three or four times higher than this figure later.
The old adage "better prevent than cure," particularly applies in the case of monetary policy.
If one judges by the outcome of last month's meeting of the ECB Council of Governors, this "prevention" appears close to a major step for the economy of the Eurozone.
Indeed, the pace of warnings of the ECB on the risks of inflation has accelerated in recent months, and what was a "to be vigilant" has become a "are very vigilant" in September, before turning into "accrued vigilance about the high risks to price stability" in October.
The Council of Governors risks finding itself short of adjectives and credibility, if it does not act soon.
The tone of the comments by ECB President Jean-Claude Trichet during the question and answer session of the press conference following the meeting in October was particularly aggressive.
Mr Trichet seemed to appeal to a preemptive approach when he said: "We must not let the side effects materialise."
For the first time, the ECB president was willing to admit that the governing council had discussed advantages and disadvantages of an increase in interest rates during its meeting.
However, current interest rates are described as "still up in the air" in October, which indicates that the ECB has not yet made the decision to take action.
It is certain that an unexpected slowdown in economic activity or a sharp increase in the value of the Euro could postpone the inevitable increase in interest rates.
What seems to have emerged clearly is that the ECB has used the press conference from October to warn the politicians, unions and the markets that its long period of inactivity on monetary policy is nearing its end.
The end process is underway.
Not everyone is thrilled with this news.
Politicians, including Jacques Chirac in France, Silvio Berlusconi in Italy and Ecofin (the finance ministers of the member states of the European Union), continue to call for fixed rates, and even always lower rates.
But it is easy for politicians to act irresponsibly when it comes to monetary policy.
They are not being singled out when prices go up, any more than they are supposed to put the genie of inflation back in the bottle.
By pushing constantly for a rate cut larger than what the ECB can offer, political authorities make the ECB the scapegoat for the mediocre economic performance in Europe.
Europe is going badly, they say, not because of their own failure to conduct the required structural reforms, but because the rates are too high.
At the same time, the ECB does not have to go as far as the Federal Reserve, which has raised its key interest rates with an increase of 25 basis points over the course of 12 consecutive meetings, with further increases predicted.
For the ECB, an increase of 50 basis points would suffice at this stage, and rates could then be put on hold for some time.
The Fed waited too long to start the process of normalisation, and,as a consequence, has been more aggressive in lowering rates in the downward phase of the cycle of interest rates, and thus, had to be more aggressive in raising them in the rising phase.
This is not the kind of volatile monetary policy Europe wants, nor is what it needs.
The West against the rest of the world?
The bombings in Madrid have brought the scourge of terrorism to the gates of Europe.
March 11, from now on, represents the European version of the American September 11.
However, America and Europe often seem not to see the world with the same view: Spain's answer to terrorist attacks, a threat that affects all democracies, was to elect a government promising to end the American-led policy in Iraq.
Should we then understand that Europe and the United States have considerably different visions?
The apparent division  on foreign policy is partly due to a misunderstanding about the nature of "Europe".
The European project represents the realistic answer to globalisation and its challenges.
It was launched to create "solidarity", to promote political stability and strengthen democracy and the social model of Europe.
Having achieved these goals, Europe now wishes to make a positive contribution to the developments of the world.
This is not nostalgia for a past glory.
An unprecedented solidarity is now spreading across Europe, manifesting itself for example in collective grief and expressions of compassion towards Spain; we must use this vast potential as a basis to create a sense of solidarity in the world.
The United States, also victims of a horrific attack, feel drawn to the world, without going to promote a similar pattern of cooperation.
In defending their values and their security, Americans strive rather to  defend the world, most particularly the Western world, from new dark threats.
The messianic idealism which has delivered Europe from Nazism and has protected Western Europe from communism is now headed towards other enemies.
All the attention being focused on tense transatlantic relations, it is easy to forget that our concerns often meet.
On issues such as terrorism, the proliferation of weapons, Iran, Afghanistan (a country in which we train together with the future army) and Africa (where the French initiatives and American support have recently allowed the stabilization of the Ivory Coast and the Congo), Europe and America speak with one voice.
But on certain issues, such as the war in Iraq, Europeans are not ready to blindly follow America.
The world, and Europe in particular, have a fascination and admiration for the United States.
But today, we must reject all sentiment of fascination and gratitude and realize that the pursuit of European integration is in the interest of the United States, who has supported it for 50 years.
In the today's world, there is enough work for two to bring stability and security, and to promote shared values.
In particular, Europe's Franco-German "engine" should not be regarded as a potential rival for the United States.
France and Germany are not forming an axis aspiring to become a kind of leadership alternative to the United States.
The two countries are rather a laboratory necessary to the internal functioning of the EU.
Anyone who thinks that we produce a European rival to America has not considered properly the facts.
Indeed, France and Germany do not naturally get on.
There are many differences between them : the expansion of the EU, agriculture and the national market.
It is therefore not there.
This is why I do not believe in the imminence of a lasting break.
Most Americans still see Europe as a partner with largely the same goals in the world.
The majority of Europeans see in America a reliable friend.
We are all allies of the US; our growth strategy and our contribution to global stability depend on the unique nature of our relationship with America.
This is why the US should encourage the development of a European security and defence policy, which is simply the share the burden that America has imposed on Europe for decades.
We must forge greater European military capabilities to establish a mechanism that allows us to put ourselves side by side effectively when terrorism or other catastrophes strike one of our democracies, as has just happened.
But we also must create a capacity for independent European military planning because the EU might need to lead its own operations, perhaps because NATO is reluctant about this.
We, the French, are opposed to Europe being a " two-speed " institution.
But we want a structured cooperation (i.e., some European countries can urge the establishment of a defense capability) because we are not prepared to let the most prudent and the most cautious among us to repeat the Balkan tragedy of the 1990s, when the Europeans could not act and the Americans didn't want to (for a while).
The creation of such a capacity would make the EU a more effective transatlantic partner.
It is thus difficult for Europeans to understand why the plans for a closer European integration are seen as anti-American.
The only way to remove these fears is to establish a dialogue more closely and more often.
On the defence and security issues, the doctrine of security of the EU offers a great opportunity to consolidate our common concerns: terrorism and nonproliferation, but also the need to ensure a sustainable development in all regions of the world.
Europe and America must pursue their goals of cooperation, while ensuring that this never becomes an alliance of "the West against the rest of the world."
Some Western countries have tried to create a "clash of civilisations" based on our troubled times.
Our task is to find a way to stand up together without targeting a country in particular.
Is India ready to fully convert its currency?
It is very probable that the political audacity shown by India in its quest for peace with Pakistan in order to put an end to their nebulous clash for half a century over the conquest of Kashmir will be matched by equally bold economic initiatives.
Indeed, India is progressing slowly towards a truly courageous reform: the full international convertibility of the rupee.
This convertibility will affect not only economic development in India, but will give a lesson to China which is considering convertibility in the coming years.
Since 1991, India has fluctuated between the devaluation of the rupee and full convertibility, the Reserve Bank of India (BIS) easing a number of foreign exchange controls.
Indian residents can now own foreign currency accounts and invest in shares of foreign companies, while non-resident Indians can repatriate legacies/inheritances.
Indian companies listed on foreign exchanges can acquire property in foreign countries and resident companies are entitled to pay in advance the external commercial debt up to 100 million dollars.
The limits placed on foreign exporter accounts are removed and banks can invest in overseas capital and money markets.
Is India ready for a full convertibility?
The government is always behind as far as the national economic reforms.
Structural reforms and privatization slowed down, undermining investor confidence.
But this inability to address structural problems could expose the economy to external shocks in the long term.
It would be premature for India to open up its capital account immediately.
The stability of exchange rates is the major anchoring point when a country's reform process has begun.
However, it remains unlikely that convertibility of the capital account has a significant impact on the growth rate of a country.
With capital account convertibility, the exchange rate of the rupee will be determined more by capital flows than by differences in inflation rates, given that India’s inflation rate corresponds more or less with the average of 3% for the OECD.
Since India is still in a deficit, the rupee could be subjected to pressure following a negative shock.
Although the monetary growth stands at more than twice the rate of real GDP growth, the risk of inflation would probably be low because of a substantial excess capacity.
Indeed, the 1990's, despite an overall yield increase, have experienced significant deflation that implies that the overall performance potential of India is developing.
The steps towards the full convertibility of the capital account have continued to match the massive growth of currency reserves of India.
Indeed, the availability in foreign currencies of India have considerably grown over the last decade.
Following a surplus capital account and a gap of interest rates of 3-4%, the currency reserves have reached 70,3 billions of dollars in late 2002, enough to cover about 15 months of imports, compared to only $4 billion in 1990.
Following the balance of payments crisis in 1991, the exchange rate of the rupee has been devalued by 20%.
Exporters could exchange 30% of their profits according to market conditions.
This method has subsequently been replaced by a system of double exchange rates, which made the rupee partially convertible (60% of revenues derived from exports could be converted at market exchange and the rest, according to a fixed rate of the RBI, used by the government to finance imports of goods such as gasoline, cooking oil, fertilisers and lifesaving drugs).
The dual exchange rate acted as a tax on exports, but it didn't last long, yielding to a unified exchange rate with respect to trade.
The full convertibility of the current account has followed in August 1994.
The political debate is then turned toward the convertibility of the capital account, greatly encouraged by the IMF and the World Bank.
In May 1997, the Tarapore Committee on Capital Account Convertibility laid out a process of liberalization in three stages from now to 1999-2000, with an emphasis on fiscal consolidation, a set rate of inflation target and a solid financial system.
The fiduciary crisis of East Asia then put the designated stocks on hold and raised serious questions about the date of the resumption of trading and the need to pursue convertibility.
The sudden melting of apparently healthy economies bluntly reminded us that full convertibility should not arise from strong external liquidity.
After all, the liberalisation of the capital account could lead to instability in the change rate and even countries whose availability in currencies are important may not be able to prevent a rush on their reserves.
India must learn the following lesson: in case of national or external shock, the full convertibility could prove to be a costly and ephemeral experience.
The key question is whether a full convertibility would encourage the income or expenses of net capital funds.
The risk of greater instability for the rupee is compounded by serious problems, including a deficit equal to 6% of GDP and the impasse with Pakistan.
The movement of short-term capital, likely to happen if one of these two risks got worse, could make the overall outcome even more unstable.
So it is vital for India to increase the amount of long-term capital, as the capital account will be closed or opened.
In this context, it is remarkable that China, which has a closed capital account and reserves totaling $286 billion, or four times that of India, has an economy that's only twice the size of India's.
Full convertibility is not the key to attracting more significant direct investments (FDI) abroad.
China has attracted FDI of 52,7 billion dollars in 2002, the greatest return of capital in the world.
India needs more important FDI to absorb the excess capacity of its economy.
This situation underlines the importance of the successful management of the capital account (control of revenue and the movement of capital) for India after a first step towards full convertibility.
But in the short term, full convertibility of the capital account is not in the interests of India.
The Chancellor's Twilight ?
The resignation of Chancellor Gerhard Schreder as president of the Socio-Democratic Party of Germany will profoundly affect the distribution of forces within the German government and its weak "red green" majority in Parliament.
Although it seems premature to speak, as some do in Germany, of the "twilight of the Chancellor" or to refer to Schreder's surprising decision as the "start of the end" of his political position, it is perfectly appropriate to describe it as a consequent loss of power.
The main winner is Franz Mentefering, the 64 year old leader of the parliamentary delegation of the Social Democratic Party, who will succeed Schreder as President of the party.
The two politicians will rule in tandem, but Schreder will depend more on the loyalty of Mentefering than Mentefering will depend on the success of Schreder.
Schreder represents a platform and a moderate left political program similar to the philosophy of the New Labor’s British Prime Minister Tony Blair or centrism of the former American president Bill Clinton.
Mentefering is, however, more attached to the traditional values of the social democratic party (or the former Labour Party).
In terms of styles of leadership, Schreder plays solo, Mentefering as a team.
In Germany, the Chancellor occupies the highest position among the main political players.
The main source of strength to a German chancellor does not reside, however, in the legal powers that were conferred to him by the constitution, but in the real support gathered in his own party.
With one notable exception in the 1950s, neither of the two main political parties in Germany (the Social Democrats and the moderately conservative Christian Democrats) has ever succeeded in obtaining an absolute majority in Parliament.
In consequence of that, the German chancellors and president generally form coalition governments and their real authority is founded on the loyalty of the party forces they command in these political alliances.
Although Social Democrats have never really appreciated Schreder (they certainly don't appreciate him as much as the unforgettable Willy Brandt), they have followed him willy-nilly while they have considered him as the only guarantor of electoral success after 16 frustrating years (1992-1998) in opposition to Helmut Kohl.
But things have changed.
Since the end of 2002, Schreder and the SPD have found themselves confronted to unusually low rates of voter approval and this situation is not close to changing.
Over the course of the single year 2003, about 40,000 Social Democrats left their party, a hemorrhage without precedent.
If the national elections had been set for last Sunday, the 8th of February, a coalition of the center-right made up of Christian Democrats and Liberals would have received 57% of the votes, according to Infratest dimap, one of the main polling organizations in Germany.
With a maximum 35% votes, Schräder's "red green" coalition would have run to its loss.
At the beginning of what was called "a super election year" for Germany (14 elections, one European, five regional and eight local), it was shaping up to be catastrophe news for the SDP.
Several times, Schreder had been extremely stimulated by the desperate situations when he was back to the wall.
This quality is greatest strength and it would seem that has now launched the most risky possible counter-offensive.
It is based on the following bet: a significant economic improvemment will happen beginning in the second half of 2004 until the next national elections in autumn 2006 and the voters will attribute this expected recovery to economic, labor market and welfare state reforms,called "Agenda 2010," which Schraeder had made the spearhead of his chancellery.
For a long time, Shroeder's reformist rhetorics did not match his politics.
It was only after his reelection in the autumn of 2002 that he abandoned his former populist position, his short-term solutions and his neo-corporatist methods aimed at convincing the unions and the employers' associations.
Given the more pressing problems in Germany (an accelerating demographic decline, an excessively regulated labor market and a confusingly obscure fiscal system), Schroeder's reform program may seem far too timid, but numerous decreases have been perceived as extremely harsh by the most significant electoral constituency of the SDP, and particularly by the powerful trade unions.
But, considering the distressed economic situation in Germany, which should worsen because of the country's demographic problems, the social democrats have no choice now but to give up creating wealth in favor of its redistribution.
Germany cannot afford to become idle or, even worse, to stop the reform process.
In the best case scenario, Schrader would remain faithful to the philosophy of "Agenda 2010" and Mantefering would patiently explain to an rather ill-disposed SDP that they would have to cross the desert before arriving at the Promised Land.
In the worst case, Schrader will return to populism to win an electoral victory in the short term and Müntefering will endorse this choice to avoid having the wounded Social Democrats party fall into absolute despair.
Schraeder's tragedy is that his power could collapse further, no matter which path he chooses.
At the end of the present "super election year," we will know the answer.
The great man Syndrome
In this era of globalization, it is large, impersonal forces that are supposed to determine the course of events.
The globalization of markets, unfettered trade, militant Islam, China's awakening: these are the things historians and strategists usually portray as the key forces shaping our destiny.
Yet for most, we do not see things as well.
Most people will always instinctively look for "great men" for historical figures, the men (and women) who seem to shape events through their political vision, their personal charm and the strength of their moral views.
With the simple force of their convictions and their personalities, such figures, we believe, can stimulate progress, by providing a glimmer of hope in a universe which is otherwise detached and impersonal.
This need to find providential  men or women in this era of globalization results from three factors.
Initially, it is a question of the complexity and the vulnerability of our world.
Then, paradoxically, it is about our ever-growing criticism of politics and politicians.
Finally, it is the result of our media obsessed culture that she is to put a "face" on the events.
Faced with the problem of getting positive changes in a national or international environment that seems to defy the power of "ordinary" leaders, we then turn to new Alexanders to untangle the "Gordian knot" and transcend the complexity of the simple strength of will and dynamism.
Structural reforms in Europe, for example, are considered impossible to implement unless they are imposed by a reincarnation of Margaret Thatcher.
In the Middle East, everyone awaits the arrival of a new Anwar Sadat in the Arab world.
The disillusionment with the political world and politicians is an equally important element in our hopes for a beneficent leader.
In France, for example, the slightly too flattering celebration of the tenth anniversary of the death of François Mitterrand mainly reflects the general disillusion felt towards his successor, Jacques Chirac.
The indirect criticism of the present is often a key element of an idealized vision of the past.
The less we demand a "normal" politician, the more we are looking for a hero.
Now that the world has become an international stage, the role of the media in feeding this appetite for propitious leaders is essential.
The public calls for quick responses to complex problems that, if they remain unresolved, could endanger the planet.
He needs figures with which it can identify, that it can immediately recognize and, above all, in which he can trust.
The emergence of a "global civil society" embryonic exacerbates the requirement of universal figures and charisma, representing of a hope of world-wide accountability, with certain populist overtones.
In a world in search of providential leaders, the case of Ariel Sharon is symbolic and paradoxical, because this universal man remains one of the most controversial figures in recent decades.
He has become a man almost revered in his country and Western public opinion generally sees his political defeat as representing a blow that could be fatal for any hope of progress in the region, even if he remains loathed in many parts of the Arab and Muslim world.
The transformation of Mr. Sharon, the traitor who became a hero within a few years, is a source of fascination for his people, the region and the world, especially as his basic intents will remain forever open to discussions for tomorrow's historians and politicians who would claim to be his true heirs today.
Has Mr. Sharon really been convinced by the demographers that the "Great Israel" that once seemed to be his prime aspiration really means the end of the Jewish State and does his strategy of disengagement, which is based on "Gaza before all else," really mean "Gaza only"?
For those who support one or the other of these interpretations, Mr. Sharon will never be accorded the benefit of the doubt.
The fact that one could compare the attack Mr. Sharon suffered, in terms of political consequences, to the assassination of Yitzak Rabin demonstrates just how much we associate his persona with hope and security.
The "bulldozer" has become the grandfather of most Israelis and the last asset of Western diplomacy for Americans and, surprisingly, for Europeans as well.
He alone seemed to embody the necessary combination of strength and vision to assemble a majority of Israelis behind him in a process of unilateral disengagement.
In fact, one wonders if the world has not made a savior out of  Mr Sharon because he wanted to believe against all odds that there was still hope in the Middle East.
Was it a futile illusion or a prophecy that is being fulfilled ?
We will never know.
What is certain is that the vacuum created by the departure of Mr Sharon from political life is all the more striking in light of the images of chaos that emerges from Gaza since Israel's withdrawal and the collapse under our eyes of the Palestinian Authority.
No more than the emergence of a new providential personality will be easy.
Not every exceptional period creates its own Bonaparte, which is probably for the best, because exceptional leaders can convey the impression that all problems have solutions, which is far from being true.
The natural course of history at its most optimistic is still the progress which occurs "on the periphery," but the fast pace of technological change leads us to expect the same sort of progress in human affairs.
Many of us believe that such an impossible bet may be fulfilled by only a providential man, with all the hopes and the dangers, that it represents.
The fall of the UN
The reign of terror of Saddam Hussein is coming to an end.
His ba' athist government will not sink alone however.
Ironically, the United Nations down with him.
It is possible that the UN would not disappear completely.
The sectors dedicated to "good works" (i.e., bureaucracies to maintain low risk peace or those that fight against AIDS and malaria or to protect the rights of children) will remain.
The chatterbox arising from New York's East River will continue to moan.
The reluctance of the Security Council to endorse the use of force to enforce its own resolutions on Iraq's possession of weapons of mass destruction tolled the end of the decades-old fantasy that the UN was the basis of world order.
While we reject the remnants of the war to liberate Iraq, it is important to preserve, through international law applied by international institutions, the intellectual wreckage of the liberal concept of security in order to better understand them.
While free Iraqis describe the nightmare of Saddam's rule, which lasted a quarter century, we must not forget those who supported this war and those who did not, those who said that the moral authority of the international community was chiselled into pleas with the aim to obtain additional delays for the UN inspectors and those who demonstrated against the "regime change."
In the spirit of an after-war reconciliation that diplomats always want to promote, we should not resign ourselves to the old-fashioned and timid notion that the world order requests us to back down when faced with rogue states that terrorise their citizens and threaten ours.
Decent, thoughtful and full of principles, the millions of individuals who have demonstrated against the resolution to ask  Iraq for explanations were catalysed by the idea that only the UN Security Council had the necessary authority to justify the use of force.
A voluntary coalition of liberal democracies prepared to send their soldiers to stop the evil is not enough.
It doesn't matter that these troops will apply the UN requirements.
If a country or a coalition of countries other than the UN Security Council made use of force, even as a last resort, "anarchy" and not the international law, the sets, destroying any hope of world order.
This is what the demonstrators believed.
But this idea is dangerously wrong and leads inexorably to justify morally (and even to justify decisions politico-military existential) countries like Syria, Cameroon and Angola, Russia, China and France.
If a policy is right when the Security Council approves it, how can it be wrong, simply because the communist China, Russia, France or a multitude of secondary dictatorships refuse their approval?
Those who are opposed to the actions of the coalition in Iraq generally respond that "order" must take precedence over "anarchy."
But is it exact?
Does the UN Security Council represent the most competent institution for ensuring order and save us from anarchy?
History suggests otherwise.
The UN was born in the ashes of a war that the League of Nations has proved unable to prevent.
The league was simply not ready to face Italy in Abyssinia, and even less, if it had survived that debacle, to fight against Nazi Germany.
In the euphoria that followed the victory during the Second World War, hope to make collective security was placed in the hands of the Security Council of the UN, with ineffective results.
During the Cold War, the Security Council turned out to be completely paralysed.
In fact, the decision to defend South Korea in the attacks against it in 1950 was taken by the Council only because Stalin had ordered its diplomats to boycott sessions of the UN, implying that no Soviet Ambassador was present to exercise his veto rights.
This was a mistake that the Soviets would not commit any more.
In 1967 and 1973, the UN pulled out of the Middle East, leaving Israel to defend itself by its own resources.
The Soviet empire was brought down and Eastern Europe liberated, not by the UN but by the mother of all coalitions, NATO.
Faced with multiple attacks by Milosevic, the UN failed to put an end to the Balkan wars or even to protect its victims.
Do you recall Sarajevo?
of Srebrenica and of the massacre of thousands of Muslims under the false protection of the UN?
It took countries of good will to create a coalition to save Bosnia from extinction .
Once the war was over, peace was agreed in Dayton, Ohio, and not at the UN.
The rescue of the Muslims of Kosovo was not due to the UN: their cause had never received the approval of the Security Council.
This century is now presenting a challenge to hopes for a new world order based on a new set of blueprints.
We will neither win against nor contain the fanatical terror if we do not bring war to territories that trigger it.
We must for this use force against states who give refuge to terrorists, as we have done to destroy the  Taliban regime in Afghanistan.
The most dangerous states are those which possess weapons of mass destruction, chemical, biological and nuclear weapons which can kill not hundreds or thousands of people, but hundreds of thousands.
Iraq was one of them, but there are many others.
The hope to convince them to withdraw their support or asylum they give to the terrorists is based on certainty and efficiency they face.
The chronic inability of the Security Council to implement its own resolutions regarding Iraq, is clear: it is simply unable to fulfill its mission.
We therefore remain solely with the coalitions formed by countries of goodwill.
Far from denigrating them as a threat to a new world order, we should instead recognize that they are, by default, the best hope that remains for this order and the real alternative to the anarchy engendered by the deplorable failure of the United Nations.
Neoliberalism, and then?
Twenty years of neoliberal economic policies have provided nothing but disappointing results for developing countries.
Latin America, the region that has most tried to implement the proceeds of the "Washington Consensus" (free market, deregulation, privatisation), has experienced low and volatile growth that widens the gap of inequality.
Among the former socialist economies of Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, few have managed the actual production levels achieved before 1990.
In sub-Saharan Africa, most of the savings have failed to address the adjustment programs required by the IMF and World Bank.
The rare examples of success occurred in countries which followed their own pace and which do not really reflect an Epinal-type image of neoliberalism.
China, Vietnam and India: all three have disobeyed virtually all the rules of the handbook of the perfect neo-liberal, even when they embarked on an approach geared more toward the markets.
It is now time to drop neoliberalism and the Washington consensus.
It remains to challenge an alternative, a set of policies with the aim to promote development without falling into the trap of a new  unworkable plan allegedly planned for the well-being of all countries without distinction.
Experience suggests that an adequate program of growth must be rooted in two strategies: an investment strategy designed to revive growth in the short term and a strategy for setting up institutions, designed to give a strong economy facing adversity some economic shocks.
The key to an investment strategy is to get local businessmen interested in the local economy.
Encouraging foreign investment or clinging to total liberalisation and then waiting until the situation improves itself is not viable.
An effective strategy must achieve two objectives: to encourage investment in relatively untraditional areas and to curtail those projects or investments that do not work out.
For that, governments must use both the carrot and the stick.
Finding out what a country easily produces (or could produce) is the main challenge of all economic development.
The policy of the carrot is necessary because there is much to gain socially if we discover, for example, that cut flowers, soccer balls or computer programs can be produced at lower cost. Also because this knowledge can guide the investments of other entrepreneurs.
The businessman who makes the first "discovery" can only capture a small part of the social value that this knowledge generates, and rapidly, it is followed on this path by others.
Consequently, entrepreneurship of this type (finding out what can be produced) is usually under-represented because of a lack of trade incentives.
It is necessary as well to use the policy of the stick to ensure that these incentives do not generate useless or barely productive investments.
The establishment of such a strategy may vary from one country to another, according to its administrative capabilities, the system of incentives that prevails, the flexibility of its tax system, the degree of sophistication of its financial sector and the underlying political economy.
The funding programmes limited in time, the funding of public companies and the financing of exports account for some ways to approach this, but there are many others.
There is no unique way which worked everywhere.
The governments that do not possess the skills required to exercise their role as director of private sector head straight to catastrophe and have little chance of improving the allocation of resources.
This attempt can succeed, but economic growth requires more than the temporary resuscitation of investment and entrepreneurship.
It also requires efforts to build four types of institutions needed to maintain the progress of growth and for strengthening resilience to economic shocks:
institutions capable of building the market (right of ownership and contract law)
institutions of market regulation (outsourcing, economies of scale, professional information).
Institutions to stabilize the market (monetary and fiscal management.)
institutions which legitimize the market (social security and insurance).
However, it takes time to build and solidify these institutions.
Have an initial period of growth to try and innovate on these fields could prove highly paying afterwards.
The key here proceeds from institutional arrangements that are, by necessity, specific to each country.
Finding out what works in any country implies some experimentation.
After all, institutions are not greenhouse plants which can be replanted in any soil under any climate.
The reforms that work in one domain can turn out to be mediocre or insufficient in others.
Such specificity helps in understanding why some countries succeed (China, India, South Korea and Taiwan among others) by combining some rather unorthodox elements with policies which are wholly traditional.
It also explains why some large institutional differences persist among industrialized countries of North America, Western Europe and Japan in areas such as the role of public sector, the legislative system, corporate governance, financial markets, labor markets and social protection.
While economic analysis can help make institutional choices, public debate and collective decisions also have important roles to play.
In fact it considers the public participation democracies as meta-institutions which allow for a choice in the "menu" of institutional arrangements for each area.
To design such a growth strategy is both more difficult and easier than setting up standardised neoliberal policies.
More difficult since the constraints that it imposes on growth are often specific to each country and adapt poorly to the standard conventions.
Easier, however, because once these constraints are clearly targeted, relatively simple policy changes can help enormously in economic terms and can open the way to a virtuous circle of growth and institutional reforms.
Adopting this approach does not mean giving up a standard economic outlook, far from it.
Neo-liberalism is to neoclassical economies what astrology is to  astronomy.
In both cases, there must be a well rooted faith to move from one to the other.
Critics of neoliberalism should not oppose classical economics but only its misuse.
The other central Europe
A spectre lingers in central Europe, while its countries prepare to join the European Union.
This promising development is compromised by a heated electoral nationalism that seeks to win votes by promising to reopen old wounds and settle old scores.
The most striking example comes from Hungary, where the Prime Minister Viktor Orban has demanded the repeal of the decrees adopted in 1945 by the president Edvard Benes (who decreed that that the goods of the Germans and Hungarians deported from Czechoslovakia be confiscated and their citizenship removed) in a campaign for re-election, which has not accomplished justice.
But Orban is not the only to see an electoral advantage in evoking memories of old ghosts.
Orban has argued that the revocation of the "Benes decrees" had to be a condition of the integration of the Czech Republic (as well as of Slovakia) into the European Union.
The unwillingness brought on by the Orban's maneuver has interrupted a large part of the regional cooperation put in place during the last decade.
Instead, a new, menacing form of national populism is emerging in the plain that stretches from Bavaria and the Danube.
The chain reaction arising from the awakening of nationalism dangerously changes the political landscape.
Since the election which brought to power the coalition of the parties of Wolfgang Schüssel and Jorg Haider in Vienna, Austria's relations with the neighboring Czech Republic have deteriorated on two points: the requirement that the Czechs close the Temelin nuclear plant on the Austrian border and that they revoke the Benes Decrees under which the Sudeten Germans were deported from the Czech Republic and moved en masse to Bavaria as well as to Austria.
Once the issue of the nuclear plant was resolved, populist pressure was channeled in a single direction, the petition for the repeal of the Benes decrees.
The Czech prime minister Milos Zeman quickly demonstrated that he could also play a popularity-seeking nationalist card.
He described the Sudeten Germans as Hitler's "fifth column" and suggested that Israel could resolve its Palestinian problem by using the Czech method of 1945: namely, deportation.
The head of the Bavarian government, Edmund Stoiber, candidate of the conservative CDU/CSU for German Chancellor against current Chancellor Schroeder and a staunch defender of Sudeten Germans, has demanded that Schroeder cancel a planned visit to Prague in response to Zeman's explosive reaction.
In order to defuse an election battle with his rival, Schroeder agreed to it.
The fact that Orban had backed the demands of Stoiber was perceived as a gift from heaven by the Slovak nationalist Vladimir Meciar in his latest attempt to become Prime Minister, because it allowed him to claim that his national opponents appeared willing to yield to pressure from the European Union and to oblige Slovakia by compensating the Hungarians expelled by Benes in 1945.
Meciar then leapt ahead, denouncing the "Hungarian threat," wiping out with a single stroke four years of hard work with the current government of Slovakia to include representatives of ethnic Hungarian minorities in the government of Slovakia.
The issues relating to the legal system of post-war Europe go well beyond the former Czechoslovakia.
Erika Steinbach, president of the Association of deported (eastern) and a member of the CDU of Stoiber, sustains that the issue of deportation of German populations affects the Poles, Czechs, Slovaks and Slovenians, thus encompassing a large part of eastern Europe and central Europe.
In the 1930s the bête noire of certain countries in Central Europe was "the Treaty of Versailles."
It seems today that statements made in Potsdam in 1945 and that ratified the mass expulsion of the German people are the new enemy.
The current concern is that this type of rhetoric could lead to a cycle of populist victories.
This concern began when the Fidesz Viktor Orban party lost the recent parliamentary elections in Hungary, but other politicians delighted to become the loudest voices for national resentments - Vaclav Klaus in Prague, Edmund Stoiber in Germany, Vladimir Meciar in Slovakia - still consider nationalism a vote-getter, despite Orban's defeat.
Given that they are linked to the sceptics who oppose the European Union, such as Berlusconi in Italy and the Schüssel-Haider coalition in Austria, the true nature of European politics is decidedly at risk for becoming unpleasant.
Since its creation, the European Union has sought to move beyond the old disputes and, through cooperation, to build a better future.
Today, some politicians want to profit from Eastern Europe's desire to turn certain historical issues to their political advantage.
Such a situation presages two fatal consequences: first, that there is no more advantageous means for turning some parts of public opinion in candidate countries against the European Union than to allow the local populists to portray the Union as an agent of the spread of German power.
An expanded European Union must represent a way to balance the asymmetric relationship which exists between the little countries of Eastern Europe and Germany.
It is possible that it is perceived as an indication of this asymmetry.
The second concern is that while NATO and the European Union is expanding, these unpleasant debates may contaminate relations within the international bodies.
This fear may be one of the reasons why President Bush recently refused to meet Prime Minister Orban and it is frequently speculated that if Orban spoke as he does now before Hungary's entrance into NATO, the candidacy of his country would have been rejected.
What could possibly interrupt this process?
After 1945, Western Europe entered painful discussions on history, which contributed to Franco-German reconciliation.
The notions of "collective guilt" have been dismissed as having no basis in a unified and unifying Europe.
President Vaclav Havel expressed himself boldly during his first trip to Germany in January 1990, but his comments were miscontrued for weakness.
With the approach of the expansion of the European Union, the mission of Europe should not be contaminated by supporters of the idea that politicians of the former "other" central Europe prefer to indulge in the past rather than thinking responsibly of how to build a peaceful and prosperous Europe.
Should Bush and Blair resign?
The most important consequences of the war in Iraq are not to be looked for on the battlefield.
They will show themselves later because they depend on the merits of the arguments put forward by George Bush and Tony Blair to launch an attack against a population largely unprotected.
These arguments have been passionately debated around the world.
If they proved to be justified, war may lead to a safer world.
But if they are shown to be unfounded or cannot be verified, the war could lead to greater instability.
In this case, in order to avoid worsening the situation, the American president and the British Prime Minister should resign.
The war was not, and could not be, justified based on the fact that Saddam Hussein is a tyrant.
The justifications put forth by Bush and Blair are linked to the danger posed by Saddam's regime.
They cited four points :
Iraq has weapons of mass destruction.
These weapons constitute a serious and immediate threat.
The UN inspections did not allow this threat to be eliminated.
The war was the best way to deal with this threat.
The first argument put forward will be the easiest to check.
Bush and Blair have spoken several times about stockpiles of weapons of mass destruction and about mobile units capable of producing and using them, as well as about programs in place aiming to manufacture nuclear weapons.
They must demonstrate that they are advancing, and they must do so before an international opinion, which they think is capable of tampering evidence.
This is why independent experts appointed by the UN should examine the evidence that could be discovered.
Without any real evidence of mass destruction weapons presenting a real threat, Bush and Blair should go - regardless of the coming events in Iraq.
The second argument is trickier to prove.
Bush and Blair will have to show that the weapons of mass destruction they have found constituted a serious and immediate threat.
We know that Iraq has owned chemical and biological weapons, because the United States sold them to them.
It is not a matter of knowing whether traces of these weapons remain - they must still remain in the storage sites - but whether there is sufficient quantity to constitute a threat.
If the Iraqis are now using these weapons, it would be the proof that they were ready to be used.
It must then be determined whether they could pose a threat outside Iraq's borders and the extent to which Iraq would have used them if the current war had not taken place.
The third argument lends greatly to controversy.
Bush and Blair must prove that the UN inspections were ineffective.
They can accomplish this by giving proof that the Iraqis have managed to conceal hardware in the sites controlled by the inspectors.
There should be a systematic review of previously visited sites.
And if we find weapons of mass destruction on other sites, one will have to explain why the inspectors would not have been able to find them if the inspections had continued.
The fourth argument will be used over and over again by the propaganda of the two camps.
Was the war justified in terms of costs and results ? Was it really the last resort ?
To answer these questions, the cost of war will need to be objectively evaluated. Loss of human lives will have to be taken into account, the destruction, the appearance of other form of violence (terrorism, for example), as well as the economical impact of the conflict in Iraq and its geopolitical consequences.
To date, Bush and Blair managed to convince only part of their own public opinion.
They have served to the American people a buffet ranging from simple patriotism to chauvinism, via the manipulation of fear and the confusion between Iraq and the networks of bin Laden.
But all that has not convinced the rest of the world, who view this war with a mixture of scorn and concern.
It will be different if the four arguments presented prove to be right.
When the 13 British colonies in North America embarked on the war of independence, Thomas Jefferson estimated that he had to explain the reasons for it in the name of "respect for the views of humanity." He outlined them in the Declaration of Independence.
Such an explanation, based on a rigorous set of arguments, is also needed today.
If the reasons presented for this war were not to be confirmed, the consequences would be serious.
Propaganda, images of Iraqis cheering U.S. and British troops and astonishment to the precision of smart bombs should not hide a terrible truth: Bush and Blair have broken the peace and organized massacres premeditated against the vast majority of world opinion.
In order to attenuate the divisions on the planet, we need to strengthen the authority of the UN and change the leaders in the United States and in England.
Given its huge cost, I hope that this war will be justified. But according to current evidence, I doubt it.
If it is proven without a doubt that Iraq is stockpiling weapons of mass destruction ready for use to the point where it constitutes a serious threat, and that it is unlikely the UN inspections could detect them, we must recognize the validity of the arguments of Bush and Blair.
But even in this case, war was perhaps not the best solution, compared to a policy that would have aimed at containing the dangers posed by Iraq.
But in this case, the war will have made sense.
The idea of a totally absurd war is almost too frightening to dare to consider.
Memory and oversight of Zhao Ziyang
So the former Chinese leader and Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang has finally died.
The political choices that he had espoused during his term have long been dead: as when he appeared May 19, 1989, at Tiananmen Square just before dawn to beg, with tears in his eyes, and apologized to the demonstrators.
"I am truly sorry," he said the spectators.
"I arrived too late."
After that, he embodied a historical fantasy more than a real person.
When his bizarre and unexpected appearance on the Square was broadcast  all across China on China's central television station the following morning, on one of the last days of media coverage without censorship, the public was astonished by this fleeting moment of official, and all too human, anguish.
After all, party leaders rarely show their personal feelings in public, even less so when it means stepping away from the party line as shamelessly as Zhao did.
Such individualism corresponds neither to Leninism nor to traditional Chinese proscriptions on the behavior of high-ranking officials.
While the repression that followed those exhilarating weeks of freedom of expression and freedom of assembly reached its apocalyptic height on the nights of June 3rd and 4th, Zhao disappeared, swallowed up in the hole of Party memory  where so many other leaders had ended up since the “socialist liberation" of China.
To the discredit of the democratic world, there was virtually no head of state who protested in defense of Zhao, not even just asking for an accounting for his illegal and immoral incarceration.
Instead of that, Zhao's life was held in suspense, under house arrest, under surveillance, so conveniently forgotten, like a sort of cryogenically frozen celebrity without any hope of resurrection.
Zhao was not killed, but simply allowed to live in an old Beijing courtyard house with his family.
He was permitted to go out from time to time, but well guarded like an animal in a fairground, to go to the baths or play golf alone, one of the manifestations of the "bourgeois liberalization" that its efforts toward economic reform had allowed into China, which formerly was hermetically sealed.
The Chinese have long used the death of fallen leaders as an opportunity to show their feelings, which can no longer be expressed through an ordinary political process.
During the winter of 1976, when the leader Zhou Enlai (seen as a liberal in the Maoist hierarchy) died, tens of thousands of people spontaneously invaded Tiananmen Square, thus offering the party a great fear.
It was, of course, the death of former party leader, Hu Yaobang, a liberal of the calibre of Zhao, that launched the protests of 1989.
It is not certain that fans of Zhao express themselves in the same way.
The events of 1989 remain very sensitive and Tiananmen Square is so well protected that it is hard to imagine that a demonstration of any kind might soon take place there.
At the same time, China seems so hooked on business these days that it is hard to imagine the crowds marching for a cause which added nothing to their bottom line.
It is as if the Communist Party had overturned Marx and replaced religion with benefits in the role of the new "opium of the masses."
Few outside the poorest classes of jobs workers and dispossessed farmers appear to have the taste for political protest.
On the other hand, Zhao embodied a chapter in Chinese history in which to stand as a reformer applied not only to the economy but also to every aspect of daily life.
Before becoming leader and party leader, he experienced many areas such as the collectivization of agriculture and the separation of the party from the business world, until the laws guaranteed the rights of journalists and greater openness to the external world for ordinary people.
He was even the first Chinese leader to wear a suit and tie rather than Maoist clothing when visiting abroad and was the first to participate in open press conferences.
Although Zhao was not a visionary, nor a Vaclav Havel and Lech Walesa, and not even anti-communist, his programme in the mid-1980s addressed to the whole economic, political, cultural, media and social milieu, and it led to one of the intellectually richest and most open eras of Chinese history.
It was a tragic paradox to see the political movement which had so peacefully swept across China in 1989 end by stopping the broad evolutionary process of reform to which Zhao had dedicated his whole life.
The Party's leadership was so shaken by the trauma of June 4th that over the following years, it was difficult to determine whether reform would survive.
Then, in 1992, Deng Xiaoping set in motion one of the the fastest and most comprehensive conversions to a market economy of any society in history, which served as the catalyst for the dramatic rise of China now transformed into an economic superpower.
The death of Zhao Ziyang not only reminds us that he was treated unfairly, but also how Chinese reforms have been uneven.
For the Chinese "miracle" to really become a miracle, party leaders ought to study the legacy of the man that they are now eager to throw into oblivion.
The real risks of deficits
The deficits are back and they want revenge.
The budget deficit of the US government now stands at $455 billions, or 4.1% of GNP.
Two years earlier, the United States had predicted a budget surplus for many years.
Although slightly less affected than the US, other rich countries are foundering due to budgetary deficits.
The European Commission estimates that the deficit of the French government will reach 3.7% of the GDP this year, against 3.4% for Germany; these figures go well beyond the ceiling of the deficit (3% of GDP) defined by the Stability and Growth Pact of the euro zone.
Upon finding itself at a deficit, a country is increasing its national debt and imposes a burden on future generations.
Of course politicians prefer to hide the way in which movements of wealth between generations happen.
They are aiming in priority to resolve the immediate problems and to collect now the benefits promised.
The accountants who calculate the deficits of the governments are trying to prevent politicians from fooling us into accepting the benefits they offer without understanding the future cost.
But those who are accountable offer us no method of determining when deficits are justifiable and when they are not.
Deficits lead not only to immediate political problems, but also to issues of fairness about distributions among the generations and intergenerational risk-sharing.
No generation should be obliged to accept unnecessary economic risks imposed by another generation.
The possibility that deficits properly treat future generations depends on how the system of taxation and expenditure of government is designed.
Supporters of an uninterrupted deficit often paint it as a necessary evil to rebuild an economy in which people's confidence is crumbling.
Inspired by John Maynard Keynes, they say that some ongoing deficits will reinstall the confidence before that occurs in a recession or depression.
But it is like prescribing Prozac to a patient before he becomes suicidal.
Such arguments, although they are entirely legitimate at certain times, have limits.
The public deficits of Japan created a national debt amounting to 140% of annual GDP without producing an economic resurgence.
Indeed, the current budget deficits reflect problems in the long term which do not correspond at all to what is foreseen in the Keynesian theory.
The debates on deficits must thus be redefined in terms of major intergenerational problems over the long term.
The problems are subtle because they depend on the actions of governments to come.
In the past, some governments, when they were faced with huge national debts, "deflated" them effectively.
They have thus removed the burden on the next generation that has in fact returned to investors who have not withdrawn from the bond market with the first signs of rising prices or who have delayed the purchase of their homes while inflation would have wiped out the real value of their mortgage-backed securities.
Governments might decide once again to act this way, particularly if national debts increase further.
The resurgence of a massive inflation may seem unthinkable in the current environment, but do not forget that even a relatively modest annual inflation rate of 6% decreases the real value of a nation's debt in a little more than 6 ½ years.
It is possible that a continuous public opposition to a gradual increase in inflation does not stand up long.
Some politicians can once again succeed at anchoring the idea that inflation, in being stimulating, is a blessing for the economy.
But in addition to deficits officially measured by the current governments, there is also certain obligations that are caused by demographic change (falling birth rate) and with the prospect of payments of considerable sums for social security benefits in the future.
The reach of these obligations is monumental.
In its 2003 report, US Social Security Administration Trust Funds administrators believe that maintaining the solvency of the system of social security for the next 75 years will cost 3.5 trillion, or about the amount of the current U.S. government debt ($3.9 trillion).
The administrators of the US Medicare Trust Funds (which provide medical services to retirees) estimate that their floating bonds are now worth 5.9 trillion dollars, which is more than half of America's national debt.
The possibility of a budget shortfall in Social Security and health care is far greater in Europe and Japan because of demographics which are much more difficult to deal with.
Moreover, unlike the official national debt, obligations in terms of social services are not linked to the currency.
They constitute, rather, the promise of a certain standard of living (including the value of medical services), corrected for inflation.
No government can ‘ debunk ’ them.
But this does not mean that pensions and other social obligations are to be completely frozen.
This means that the problem is political.
Pensioners are among the most powerful lobby groups in a democracy and politicians are reluctant to confront them on such an essential issue.
We have yet to face firmly the inter-generational problems that lie at the heart of current economic dilemmas.
Our retirement schemes and our national budgets must be based on a “generational accountancy” which guarantees that the economic risk is systematically distributed between the generations.
This means that the structures of pensions and taxes must be designed to take greater account of the changing circumstances facing different generations, rather than making fixed promises, which will certainly not be able to be kept anyway, as to some degree of recovery in the future.
For example, when demographic trends or unrelenting economic hardship impose burdens on the workers with respect to social benefits, the benefits owed to pensioners must automatically be modified by increasing the retirement age and/or by benefit adjustments.
These adjustments will probably happen in the decades following, but only after a long gap and with many injustices.
We need a system which is fair from the outset in order to deal in a rational way with risks that will span several generations.
Can these problems be resolved today, when the economic downturn in most of the advanced countries leads the majority of politicians to focus on the results on the short term?
Hard times, like the Great Depression, helped bring about decisive changes.
Under an effective leadership (which unfortunately seems to be lacking), more tempered statements today could enable a public discussion on the most appropriate methods of risk sharing between the generations.
Say no to Bush
It is three years now that the American president has been pursuing a unilateral program, denying any evidence that would contradict his positions and ignoring fundamental and historic American principles.
Take the example of global warming.
In this domain, Bush is shining by its absence without permission (AWOL in American military jargon).
From time to time, he calls into question the scientific theories.
(We know, of course, that Bush's academic performance never impressed anyone.)
Bush's stance is worse than bad: it puts us in an embarrassing position.
In fact, when Bush asked the US National Academy of Sciences to consider the issue, the verdict was resounding: greenhouse gases pose a serious threat (that is surely the only verdict that they could have reached).
But the American car manufacturers love their cars that consume a lot of gas, and the Bush's friends in the oil industry will accept no interference in their destruction of the Earth's atmosphere.
Also we did not change the environmental policies.
In Iraq, Bush once again pursued a unilateral program, explaining that he was in possession of irrefutable evidence of ties between Saddam and Al Qaeda and that Saddam possessed weapons of mass destruction.
Even before the American invasion, there was overwhelming evidence proving that Bush was lying.
The detection technologies had clearly shown that Iraq had no atomic weapon, as the leader of the United Nations inspectors, Hans Blix, pointed out.
It is possible that Bush has read these reports, but they exceeded his intellectual capacities for understanding.
It is also possible that he did not believe what he read.
Nevertheless, the American policy was not based on scientific evidence.
Since the end of the cold war, America is the only global superpower.
However, she has failed to exert the kind of necessary authority to create a new world order based on principles such as equity.
Europe and the rest of the world are aware of this failure, but they do not vote at the US elections.
