The road map of China
China is poised to adopt his 11th five-year plan, setting the stage to extend what is arguably the most remarkable economic transformation in history, while improving the well-being of almost a quarter of the world's population.
Never before has the world known such sustained growth; never before had there been such a reduction in poverty.
The explanation of the long-term success of China lies partly in its unique combination of pragmatism and vision.
While much of the rest of the developing world, according to the Washington consensus, is engaged in a quest to increase GDP worthy of Don Quixote, China has once again made clear that it sought sustainable and more equitable increases of the real living standards.
China is aware that it has entered a phase of economic growth imposing huge demands on the environment that cannot last.
Unless we change course, living standards will eventually be compromised.
It is for this reason that the new five-year plan places great emphasis on the environment.
Many parts of China among the most backward grew so fast that would be a wonder if other parts of the country were growing even faster.
While this phenomenon has reduced poverty, inequality has risen, with growing disparities between urban and rural areas, and between coastal and inland regions.
This year's World Bank's World Development Report explains why inequality, not just poverty, should raise concerns as China's 11th Five Year Plan attacks the problem head-on.
The government calls for a more harmonious society over several years, and the plan describes ambitious programs for achieving this goal.
China also recognizes that what separates the least developed countries from the most developed countries is not only a difference of resources but also of knowledge.
So it established bold plans to reduce these disparities and created a basis for independent innovation.
China's role in the world and in the world economy has changed, and the plan also reflects the situation.
Its future growth will be based more on domestic demand than on exports, which means an increase in consumption.
Indeed, China suffers from an unusual problem: excessive savings.
The people save in part due to weakness in social government insurance programs: strengthen Social Security (pension), public health and education will reduce the social inequality, will increase the sense of well-being of citizens and household goods.
If it did (and, until now, China has almost always outstripped even its own high expectations) these adjustments may impose enormous pressure on a global economic system already destabilized by the United States' enormous fiscal and commercial imbalances.
If China starts to save less, as announced by its representatives, and goes on with a more diversified investment of its reserves, who is going to finance the trade deficit of more than $2 billion a day of the United States?
This is an issue to address another day, but this day is perhaps not so distant.
With such a clear vision of the future, the challenge will be in the implementation.
China is a big country, which could not have succeed so well without extensive decentralization.
But the decentralization poses its own problems.
Greenhouse gases, for example, are global problems.
While America claims that it can not afford to do anything about it, the most senior Chinese officials have acted more responsively.
Within a month after the adoption of the plan, new ecological taxes on cars, petrol and timber products have been imposed: China is using market mechanisms to resolve its environmental problems and those of the world.
But the pressures on leaders of local governments to create economic growth and jobs will be enormous.
They will be very tempted to say that if America is not capable of producing in a way to protect our planet, then how could they do it?
To translate this vision into action, the Chinese government will need strong policies, including significant increases in taxes on the environment.
While China has been transformed into a market economy, it saw develop some problems that are the scourge of developed countries: special interests obscuring the personal interests under a mask of ideology.
Some will mention the trickle-down effect: do not worry about the poor, everyone will benefit from growth.
And others opposed the policies of competition and the strict laws of corporate governance: Let Darwinism operate its wonders.
Arguments for growth will be promulgated to counter strong social and environmental policies: for example, that increasing taxes on gasoline would kill our nascent auto industry.
Such so-called pro-growth policies do not only fail to provide growth, they also threaten the entire vision of China's future.
There is only one way to avoid it: the open discussion of economic policies in order to unveil sophistry and to provide the means to implement creative solutions for the many challenges China faces today.
George W. Bush has shown how dangerous it is to abuse secrecy and restrict the decision-making process to a close circle of sycophants.
Most people outside China do not realise how its leaders, conversely, have been engaged extensive deliberations and consultations (even with foreigners) when they struggled to solve the problem with which they were faced.
The market economies are not self-regulated.
They can not simply be left on autopilot, especially if one wants to ensure that their benefits are widely shared.
But dealing with a market economy is not easy.
It is a balancing act, which must constantly respond to economic changes.
The 11th five-year plan of China provides a road map in this direction.
The world opens its eyes, full of hope and of fear, while the lives of 1.3 billion people continue to be transformed.
The lessons on democracy by Tocqueville
Because of the war in Iraq, 200 years after the birth of Tocqueville, the world debating the nature of democracy.
Tocqueville is rightly famous for having rejected the nostalgia reactionary, given that democracy is our destiny, warning, however, on the dangers it presents for freedom.
Should we share his concern?
Tocqueville did not consider democracy first as a political system, but primarily as an intellectual property that shapes the customs and traditions of society, awarding him a sociological and psychological dimension.
Tocqueville believed that democratic systems guide the course of our thoughts, our desires and our passions.
In the same way that there has been the renaissance man and the twentieth century's Homo Sovieticus, "the democratic man" is a form of human being.
For Tocqueville, the systemic effects of democracy can lead people to abandon their ability to reason.
They can only pretend to judge the events and the values by themselves, when in fact they simply repeat the reductrice views  of the majority.
Which Tocqueville called the stranglehold of the "social strength" on the opinion is doubtless stronger in the democratic systems - a view point that left to presage the level of demagoguery and of manipulation by the media in the modern world.
Tocqueville believed that over the long term, nothing can really object to this trend.
Neither local democracy, nor small groups within society, nor the counterweights, nor civil rights can prevent the decline of critical thinking that democracy seems to engender.
The school is at best an enclave away from the irresistible influence that society exerts on the mind.
Similarly, Tocqueville believed that a religious faith or the search for virtue in the ancient manner could sometimes elevate the soul, but that both were incompatible with the democratic ideal when imposed by the authorities within the framework of public life.
In this sense, the Neo-Marxist theorists of the Frankfurt and Hannah Arendt schools who feared above all the disappearance of reason in modern societies are the heirs to the thoughts of Tocqueville.
It can also be noted that the French philosopher Marcel Gauchet has called one of these recent books democracy against itself.
For these authors, the democratic way of life tends to eliminate any original thinking and prevent the emergence of a culture of good level, yielding to a mediocrity that leave people vulnerable to the enemies of democracy.
If history abounds with murderous regimes supported by cowed and deceived masses, the largest democratic country is likely to push its citizens into apathy and limit them to short-term thinking and myopic interests.
The past - despite rituals aimed at the commemoration of historical events - is masked by dependence on the present moment and the latest thing.
Even the supposedly educated ruling class is a victim of this grip.
The main problem with the democratic mentality lies in its lack of historical awareness.
As proclaimed Tocqueville, are the shortcomings of democracy make resigned pessimism  the only realistic path – but unacceptable - which is open to us?
I don't think so.
There are ways to combat what might be called the "Democratic stupidity" that is spreading today.
The first of these means is to develop an education system which forms of real critical minds, particularly through the teaching of largely neglected subjects (nowadays) like literature, history and philosophy.
If we want to create citizens who are well informed and able to think for themselves, which is essential to the functioning of a democracy, our schools need to stop running after the latest styles in courses and begin to develop the analytical skills of the pupils.
Because of their tendency to cultivate superficiality and distraction, the mass media are the main obstacle to such an education.
Today, many people spend more time during their lives in front of a television than in a classroom.
The passivity induced by mass media is the exact opposite of the active engagement of citizens that is necessary for democracy.
But it is hard to imagine that the mass media (other than quality newspapers) would, of their own volition, become a means of enhancing citizens' critical thinking.
This focus on the mass media does not come from an elitist disregard for popular culture.
It is not just a matter of popularity- Mozart was popular in his time and Shakespeare's plays attracted the poor as much the rich- but of the refusal of mass culture to challenge and provoke.
The result is indifference and widespread public passivity.
For a long time, a global media culture is growing increasingly unable to generate any criticism or to improve feelings.
Because of its lack of interest in these matters, it is a culture that threatens democratic freedoms, because it doesn't create in any way a sense of duty to society, history or the community.
Is it too late to defend oneself against a culture that blunts the spirit to that point?
Tocqueville scorned the elites of his time because of their complacency about the dangers of democracy of the masses.
Will the short-sightedness of our leaders help achieve the realization of his alarming prophecy?
