Should Putin say to his colleagues that they too could balance the intergenerational accounts of their countries by starving out the oldest of their people?
In fact, Putin would probably be well advised not to insist on the achievements of his country.
Perhaps it is better to let the vodka flow and hope for smiles in the family photo.
Nevertheless, when Putin announces to his guests that they have to pay for Russia in order to increase their own "energy security," he will perhaps finally get the respect that he so longs for.
The economy of fear.
The world economy seems to walk on water, brushing aside to shrug its shoulders of rising oil prices, the political paralysis in Europe, the unsustainable deficit of the United States, and record prices of real estate.
Could it be because, as the G8 leaders would have us believe, investors are optimistic, confident in the direction their leaders are giving to the global economy?
Or are we governed by a disease of fear, fed by certain events, such as the recent terrorist attacks in London, which maintains the long-term interest rates low, masking a whole set of latent problems ?
The role of the extremely low (after adjusting for inflation) long-term interest rates, which hide a multitude of weaknesses in the world economy, is all too apparent.
The rise in property prices across the world is sustaining the demand in many countries, and, according to a recent study of the International Monetary Fund, continually falling interest rates explain two-thirds or more of the international rise in prices.
Europe has less benefit, but its savings would have a worse if long-term interest rates were back to their average of 25 years ago.
Similarly, Latin America is experiencing a boom in recent years, despite the burden of debt and a mixed political reform.
The weak long-term interest rates have allowed the region to manage its debt, while demand has helped drive up the price of its commodity exports.
Why did the surge in oil prices not bring the global economy on its knees, as was so often the case in the past?
Once again, the answer lies in low interest rates.
Usually, a sudden surge in oil prices translates soon as expectations of high inflation, followed by the rise in interest rates for all the dates.
But this time, the Federal Reserve continues to push up its short-term lending rates to control inflation, and the long-term interest rates, which are far more important, have declined as if by magic.
Indeed, America is the single biggest beneficiary of this cycle of low interest rates, where everyone borrows money as if soon there would be none.
Property owners, supported by rising housing prices, accumulate debts.
The federal government has thrown all fiscal prudence out the window.
The country as a whole absorbs an incredible three-quarters of world savings.
But, as long as interest rates remain low and growth stays high, the Americans can laugh in the faces of those who predict that their excesses are planting the seeds of their downfall.
But if weak long-term interest rates help so many economies walk on water, why are the rates so low and will this situation continue?
The situation is perhaps more fragile than many politicians would have us believe.
People perhaps feel less, not more secure, about their long-term future, either because they fear terrorism, a global pandemic or a set of severe financial crises.
I do not say that investors are hysterical, but simply that they have become a little more concerned about the long-term prospects.
Therefore, they rush on stocks and mortgage securities that they perceive, rightly or wrongly, as safe.
We have no other convincing explanation.
It is certain that emerging markets have a unusual savings , reforming their reserves and improving their balance the budget, but nobody expects that to continue indefinitely.
Even the director of the US Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, the Oracle of Delphi on interest rates, says about the current situation that it is a "mystery".
History suggests that the technology boom has not completely finished playing its role, and with U.S. productivity gains likely to radiate the world, raising growth rates everywhere.
Usually, a rapid global growth is reflected in interest rates to rise for the long term, unless, of course deep down, people have become concerned.
Let's suppose that investors are mindful of the possibilities of disaster in five to ten years.
(According to experts on nuclear terrorism and pandemics, the risk is real.)
Suppose that investors believe that growth will probably remain strong, but maybe -- just maybe -- the situation will disintegrate.
In this case, it "SetPoints" quite possible for low interest rates to coexist with strong growth.
It is true that some economists refer to the halcyon days of the 1950s and early 1960s, when Europe, the United States and Japan, prospered, but interest rates generally remained well below the rate of economic growth.
This period representing the golden age of global growth, why worry if we are experiencing the same phenomenon today?
What optimists forget is that these paradise-like years represent equally a period of great insecurity.
Many were those who feared the outbreak of World War III, and rightly so, according to many historians.
In that time, the specter of the Apocalypse helped keep the loans at an affordable rate.
Fortunately, the worst fears of investors have not come to pass, and we can only hope for the same thing today.
But if uncertainty is one of the main reasons that interest rates are low, then the G8 leaders should be less quick to congratulate themselves.
The fragility of collective psychology of investors is well known.
If they do one day calm down, interest rates will rise again and this could lead to ferment the latent imbalances in the world economy.
Political earthquake in Israel.
The political world of Israel is going through the most impressive changes it has seen in 30 years.
The realignment of parties and leaders is particularly worthy, given the unexpected nature of recent events: Ariel Sharon's decision to leave the Likud, the defeat of Shimon Peres as head of the Labour Party and the withdrawal of Labour members of the grand coalition government of Sharon.
It is even more important to understand the significance of these changes for the future of Israel, of the region, and of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
Basically, the Israeli political system is approaching the end of its second era.
From independence in 1948 until 1977, the Labour Party dominated until giving way to an opposition coalition of conservative, nationalist, and centrist parties allied in to the Likud bloc.
Since that time, the two parties have succeeded in power in turn, sometimes in the framework of large coalitions and sometimes in partnership with smaller parties.
On the surface, the rivalry between the parties played between "left" and "right," or "hawks" and "doves."
The truth, of course, is more complex.
Social class and economic problems, in the shadow of more persistent existential anxiety, such as physical security and sustainability of the state, have played a far lesser role in Israel than in other societies.
Here, the political divide could be defined as the clash of "optimists" and "pessimists."
The first, Labour, believed that one day a force would take root among Arabs and Palestinians ready to make peace on reasonable grounds, while the latter, Likud, were more circumspect.
For some years, the discussion was abstract, a debate on what could happen in the future, until the Oslo accords with the PLO in 1993 put the opposing views to the test.
Since 2000, when the PLO leader Yasser Arafat rejected a political agreement and in its place launched a five-year terrorist war, few optimists remain.
The intellectual realignment that resulted in Israel gave birth to a new national consensus.
It is now widely accepted that, as has always stressed the left, Israel must be prepared to withdraw from West Bank and Gaza and accept the existence of a Palestinian state in exchange for real peace.
But it is also widely accepted that, as the right has always said, none of the partners is really ready to make peace.
In this context, Sharon has won two landslide election victories as a radical applying a moderate policy, including a total withdrawal of the Gaza Strip.
That is where Israel is today, facing a political upheaval fueled by two new elements.
First, Sharon has moved the Likud to the centre, and has made the hegemonic party, while destroying all the stereotypes on his personality, its methods and his vision of the world.
It is for the same reason that many members of the Likud party see Sharon, who helped found the party, as a traitor.
Sharon must now institutionalize his reforms, even if he needs another party to do it.
Secondly, the Labour Party has proved its bankruptcy, since its only viable leader was Shimon Peres, aged 82 years, and that his anachronistic optimism for the dove has become ridiculous.
Accordingly, and due to low turnout in the elections, party primaries were won by Amir Peretz, an outsider and a populist who wants to revive the Labour Party in highlighting the social and economic problems, which means the withdrawal of the national unity coalition with Likud.
Although he will have to form a new party, Sharon will win the next election, which he has scheduled for February.
Peretz's strategy may attract voters from other left-wing parties, but Labour will surely lose centrist voters (and those for which the national security is a priority) to Sharon.
Paradoxically, it will have a huge impact in principle, yet perhaps very modest in practice.
While Sharon has strong public support for moderate policies, Israel will be more ready than ever to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, Syria, and the Arab world in general to find a diplomatic solution to global conflict.
However, given the chaos and the paralysis that increasingly characterise Palestinian politics, this opportunity will not be seized.
The growing power of Hamas, who speak openly of their strategy to increase acts of terrorism and destroy Israel, only strengthens this trend.
You can say the same of Syria, whose radical government is turning to a dangerously risky militarism.
Sharon could decide the partial withdrawal and the dismentling of West Bank settlements.
But it is today widely acknowledged that such changes are a reaction to bleak prospects for real progress toward peace.
Hanging on to land to the challenges of a bargaining has much less sense if there is no one with whom to bargain.
Israel will, rather, continue to give priority to its own security, strengthening its defenses against terrorism and consolidating its control over the relatively small portions of the West Bank that it intends to reclaim as part of a possible diplomatic accord.
As a secondary consequence of this strategy, coupled with Palestinian attacks, international sympathy has only grown towards Israel.
This phenomenon could persist if the current political realignment lasts, enabling Sharon to advance his centrist or even centre-left programme.
Nothing is assured, of course.
Benjamin Netanyahu, who remains popular, may well become a powerful rival to his right, and Peretz may well make the Labour Party a strong contender to his left.
Nevertheless, the national consensus has changed, shaking all assumptions about Israeli politics.
The February elections will put these certitudes to their toughest test in decades.
