Olmert would give back in exchange for peace almost all occupied territories
Ehud Olmert, president of the Isreali provisional government, has ruled in favour of the return of almost all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, east Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made that statement in an interview published on Monday in the daily newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth.
"We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to give back almost all the territories (occupied), maybe all," Olmert told the journal.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), because without it, peace will not happen," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants to be safe in Jerusalem, and particularly does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to relinquish parts of Jerusalem," noted Olmert alluding to the two attacks in the city, in July, during which several people were killed and dozens of people injured.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historic sites" located inside the Old City.
"Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the whole city will have to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
"That will not work," he emphasized thereafter.
Withdrawal from Golan Heights
Olmert also ruled in favour of the retreat of Israel from the Golan Heights, which is, according to him, an indispensable condition for a peace agreement with Syria.
It also would require some efforts by Damascus.
"I do not propose to make peace with Syria only on the basis of a retreat from the Golan Heights," he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan Heights.
They are going to abandon their current relations with Iran; they are going to abandon their relationship with the Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they are going to abandon the ongoing support they give to the terrorist activities of Hamas (Shiite movement) and al-Qaeida (terrorist network), as well as that given for Jihad (holy war) in Iraq, the prime minister said.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards inside buses illegal?
The law is ignoring them; walking in a long distance coach is forbidden.
In the context of the tragic accident of Student Agency coach near Padua, Italy, the question has arisen of whether the crew and passengers can move around inside the bus during the journey.
"If we wanted to respect the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is contrary to the traffic law," said the spokesman of the Department of Transportation Karel Hanzelka.
The accident, during which a 22-year-old hostess was killed, was apparently caused by a truck driver who crossed the road in front of the bus.
The girl was at this time unfortunately seated next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she has available two other seats.
But the coach can have an accident or even slow down suddenly, also at the time when the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
What matters is whether the bus satisfies its technical requirements by being equipped with standing room space or not.
If this equipment for standing places is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
Student Agency long distance coaches do not have standing seats; that was confirmed by the company's director Radim Jančura to Aktuálně.cz.
"It is an issue that we have dealt with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of the passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we arranged for passengers to be able to go to the toilet during the journey on condition that they have their own seats," he said, revealing his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no clear legal interpretation of the role of Steward - no legal regulation deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits a carrier from offering services.
The laws relating to highway transport only contain the term recipient of vehicle; they do not define his/her rights and duties," spokesman Hanzelka adds with further ambiguity.
Josef pokorný, the Head of the Road Transportation Department, believes that, at the contrary, the law tackles the issue well enough.
"It all depends on whether the coach had in his approval permission to offer standing places.
Everything lies in this," he says.
Buses are divided into urban ones, where there is standing room and a maximum speed limit, inter-urban ones with standing room and a higher maximum speed limit and long-distance buses with no standing, the highest maximum speed limit and seats fitted with seat belts.
As in the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert at BESIP (highway traffic safety) in transportation safety, does not see removal of on-board stewards as a major problem.
"With a regular circulation, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to the service in aircraft.
There neither is it sure when there will be a turbulence and the air hostess can bang her head."
"However, in the case where the coach would have slowed down briskly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in a city bus or streetcar.
The carrier needs to manage the safety of stewards by internal requirements, "he says, and he also believes that from a juridic perspective, the problem is not settled.
Jančura is ready to surpress these services
Student agency is the only coach carrier that offers services from stewards
He hires two hundred of them.
Even after this incident, the Director does not consider their profession a hazardous profession.
"However, once I have the impression that it is a risky profession, I will suppress it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper upon boarding.
That would also decrease the costs," he says.
Security concerns are the reason given by the Director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine for the absence of stewards on its ships, which results in a very reduced number of lines in comparison with SA.
"We have no receptionists. We are opposed to it since the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end by a fatal accident," he said to Týden.cz a year ago.
A great tragedy happened
A young stewardess from the Plzeň region, who had been working for the company for two years, died during the accident on the line of Naples.
A Slovenian lorry probably left the emergency stopping lane without using his turn signal and blocked the path of the coach.
The driver of the latter one tried to avoid him by using a rushing manoeuvre, but he brush against him by the right side.
Jančura denies that the two seats reserved for stewards rest were sold.
"In the case of long distance lines, it is not possible to book these places, they are blocked."
The company intends to sue the driver of the lorry.
About the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait the judgment of the court, but as regards financial compensation, it also counts on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A modification in the law, which is being developed, for more than a year, by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transportation, could provide further details regarding the stewards' shifting aboard the bus.
"However, it has not resulted in any conclusion on this point.
As a matter of fact, it has no particular interest in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phone while driving," the expert Hořín said.
"The transport ministry does not consider the activity of the stewards as something that would basically endanger the safety of passengers," concludes the spokesman Hanzelka, stating that the safety control of cars is under the power of the police and the security office at work.
