Talking in one's sleep.
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us about something that happened the day before, but children who speak in their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but in reality it does not matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep that is called somniloquy.
It is quite frequent, especially among children and teenagers.
It is sure that there is more than one who speaks during the night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause which determines its appearance
They are often linked to other alterations of sleep such as nightmares, night terrors, enuresis (bedwetting) or sleepwalking, but it is not always the case.
As we already said before, they can also be associated with very strong fever, with situations of stress or overexcitement.
Anyway it is a phenomenon little studied.
The intensity with which it happens is also very variable.
He may speak with a small calm voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with screams, tears, long speeches...
In cases where somniloquy occurs very frequently, it would be wise to observe the child and to consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem causing a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said this is a benign distortion, so there is no treatment, unless it is linked to another alteration of sleep that can be treated (e.g. if it is linked to sleep apnoea or to stress).
What we can do is be aware of a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to annoy the child before he goes to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programmes or television series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulties relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the sleep talking starts, try to stay calm.
Remember they are harmless for the child and the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Do not wake him up.
It is useless because He is unconscious and you would wake him up
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and therefore rests.
Remember that if he feels very anguished several times, it is advised to consult a doctor or check what is causing so much anxiety to the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don't be tempted to question him to obtain any information.
You will get nothing, because while sleeping, he is not aware to arrange his thinking.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming of, so be careful how you interpret information and what conclusions you draw from this.
Never say to the child that you can interrogate him during the night in order to know his secrets.
Not even in jest.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, do not worry, this is nothing really bad, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
