The "Plan North" "is the fourth part of a "vision" that the prime minister claims for Quebec, one of a new economic area, which includes an agreement on the workforce with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the speech of the prime minister recently, the opening to the North - the territory North of the 49th parallel - had never been introduced.
The prime minister, however, restricted himself to explaining why the North was "a jewel with enormous potential," but did not set a specific time, state the investment amounts or disclose the precise priority of the future projects.
At most a few avenues which could be developed further: notably hydroelectricity, the forest, but over all the mining sector, led by the growth of developing countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds," according to Mr Charest's enumeration.
This "territory twice as large as France," it is in our homeland, it is in Quebec.
