According to the English press, the government will resume its accounting of all the existing loans at the Bradford and Bringley, Bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) are mortgage loans.
The Spanish bank Santander made it known yesterday that it would buy the branches and the customer accounts of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - death of a committed icon
Her blue-eyed beauty was her trump card for a long time, some would say her weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissist's mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent which was obvious also have taken him away from the register of power that is giving birth to the real sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, deceased on Friday, at 83 years old, because of a lung cancer in his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of the American cinema of the prosperous years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he ressembles and was a long time rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also a great champion of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often brings forth beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, of a German Jew father and a mother with Hungarian origins.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without huge ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because was projected in him a whole country in love with the self made man, the Pacific war fighter, wounded in action, who in the early 1950s studied theater in Yale and then attended Actor's Studio in New York, before succeeding at the theatre, television, soon in movies.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also the race car driver, who came in second at the 24 hour mark of Le Mans in 1979, and was a sex symbol, albeit half of a model couple together with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
There also disappear with him the shadowy areas of this secretive, discreet, committed star, allergic to the glitz of show business whose enigma no one has completely unraveled.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
This weekend, the death of Paul Newman made film lovers' heads swim, as memories of all his major roles collided on their mental movie screens.
More than half a century of an always changing American seventh art  stream around him.
The cowboy charm of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) and the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958, come racing back into memory.
Closer to us (1990), his sensitive Mr Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage which did not fulfil all its promises.
Many other Paul Newman went to history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me (Marked by Hatred), by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, resumed after his death, which really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for best picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's magnificent "The Hustler" (1961), he played the role again on his return in Martin Scorsese's "The Color of Money," which won him in 1987 his only Oscar after nine nominations.
This face throughout the ages, it was him.
Him, again
The eras are jostling throughout his career.
Young people know him especially from George Roy Hill's cult film Slap Shot (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of a rather unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy from the Coen brothers.
With a final role of Irish Mafia godfather in the Road to Perdition of Sam Mendes in 2003, we had come full circle.
As opposed to several film legends who left the business rather early, Newman stayed in the saddle for a long time, all the while denouncing Hollywood, its wealth, its ostentation and its compromises.
The French film-maker Bertrand Tavernier regarded him, not without humour, "as a living challenge to 'underplaying' judging his performances as too forceful".
The profession has not always been kind to the wonderful Paul Newman whom the roles fell a long time all cooked in the tooth.
He played however less often young successful people than those on the fringe: neurotics, alcoholics, bastards or the desperate, whose perfect traits reflected mindless drifting and rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed little known aspects of his true modest nature.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (from the novel of Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the main role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his movie Harry and Son to him in 1984, a modest and sad work.
Among the deluge of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very sadly: "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generosity and love of life are vibrant features of the deceased actor.
Beyond his legendary career, we are losing a great campaigner for civil rights, ecology and independent films and an opponent of the excesses of Hollywood.
We have seen much of its face standing on vinaigrette pots, sauces, biscuits and other foods, as a process of poor taste, albeit a joke at the beggining.
The profits of these sales were nonetheless paid to his Foundation for children in difficulty.
Newman, rather than resting on his laurels, will be committed until the end.
He left to his five daughters a letter containing these words: "Always and until the end, your father has been incredibly grateful for his lucky star.
It was a privilege to be here."
And a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a coherent and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in short and above.
