Soon, on the 8th of October, will start the proceedings concerning the ongoing criminal procedure, against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud in the form of permanent and regular criminal organization, having led to rather sizable damages. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and use of forgery.
According to the public prosecutor, money from subsidies, was spent for personal gain, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the State and the municipalities, approximately 65 million HUF in total, was going on the one hand in the funds of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and, on the other hand, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, made also public by the authorities in charge of the inquiry, was to take the money of the subsidies received by issuing expense bills, for which no real provision was given and thus, the associations have never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the bills were forged.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they produced the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
As for the names of societies that were included on the bills, they were decided, among others, during tours in the province of North Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, on the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the testimony of the latter, he was supposed to identify inns and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he called for a bill, modeled on which they wrote other bills that they would introduce, among others, in the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the city hall to get subsidies.
The majority of bills was created by István lados and his accomplice Mr András Őri who, according to our information, was involved in files drafting needed to qualify for subsidies.
During a "circuit identification", one of the choices of Lados was a bistro.
According to the two bills issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place has assured the catering for a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
However, according to what the manager said, it would have been impossible that so many people fit in this place, at the same time.
Similarly, during summer 2002, the bill on behalf of Jobb Jövőért foundation which will bear the name of Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért, was full of style and spelling mistakes.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, had in fact only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill was mentioning one hundred and thirty clients.
Invoice providers with overflowing imaginations plunged into excess, when they said that the company Pigal KFT also belonged to the HORECA sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of Hoppá appears, according to the information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, said to the site hvg.hu that when the public prosecutor summoned him and showed him the bills, he knew immediately that it was forgery.
"The name of our society and our tax number were placed in the wrong spot on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the look of it, the fact that according to the bill,  a hundred people stayed there did not make sense either, since this establishment had only eleven bedrooms, which did not have enough space.
Moreover, the bill mentions meals too, and our restaurant is closed since long ago."
Zealous issuers of bills were also not well informed about Budapest's travel agencies, which were constituting a part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they said some stays in Hungary on the bills were to be paid for in cash, which also runs counter to the accounting practices of the agency.
Also, as it emerged during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the benefits on the travel activities, which the destination is outside the European Union, are charged without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four bills made out in the name of the Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's allowances do not cover a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, employees of the hotel issue only printed bills, while the false ones were made out by hand.
The prosecutor's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also erred in stating as the delivery cost highway transportation for the merchandise, which the company issuing the bills could not have performed, since it was only serving as the investment counselor.
Moreover, it is also for procedural defects, such as inadequate kinds of bills and false stamps, that bills issued by Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont turn out to be wrong.
Just as in the case of the Ravenna Bt. company or the sports resort in Kunfehértó, both of which deny being responsible for invoices issued in their names.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the HIB Kft. company, located in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have had a meal on their premises. According to our information, this is the reason why the company's liquidator denies having issued this bill.
Invoices set deliberately
Another category of issuers of bills was composed of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue false bills.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, wrote an invoice to the order of the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was asked to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, in cooperation with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued bills to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, amounting to around five million HUF, but for which no services have been rendered.
No financial movement took place, either, given that the invoices were cancelled afterward, but the organisms avoided carefully to mention this in their accounts.
The following category of companies which issued bills is that of companies directly linked to the accused.
Thus, the administrative deputy to the executive director of the Delta Trió KFT. enterprise which trades in fuel and cars, whose headquarters were located in Budapest, but where he was nowhere to be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December of 2005, this company has issued several bills for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to about 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, such equipment would have been purchased by the company Cash Investment LLC of Kiskunhalas, which was in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
This company's director was a man from Romania, whom Iván Kubatov would also have sent documents relative to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued bills on the orders of the Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány companies, and that he pocketed their exchange value.
It is precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian builders have created the Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment BT companies.
In reality, none of these companies were really operating, which the accused explained was due to the fact that they were not getting any work.
He even used those companies, because at maestro Zsolt Szente request, codefendant and editor of compagnies foundation acts, he established bills on behalf of associations reporting to Zuschlag, as Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave agencies a total of 15 bills, issued by the Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade companies, with a value of 14.2 million HUF.
The public prosecutor believed that 10% of the pointed accounts on the bills as well as VAT were going in Kubatov's pockets.
The man even used the Szi-Beri Bt. company to establish fictitious bills that were used as part of the request for a subsidy for Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant from the public utility body of the socialist party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (MRI).
They have achieved this subsidy for the sum of twice 500 Huf , but these amounts were not used for the objectives pointed in the demand.
In order to prevent it from being known, five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft. company have been presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these are bills that have been found during the raid on the office of Arpad Kemecsei, the Minister of Education.
At the hearing, part of the accused will explain bills production method, as it had already done in front of the public prosecutor earlier.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
Until now, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has promised repeatedly to tell the details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in their interest, or perhaps eventually the Socialists would together conclude that in exchange for reimbursement of a large part of the 50 million HUF, Zusi would wear only the hat.
Today, this one is probably annoyed, since the requests for his placement under house arrest, on a basis of a reduction of its detention conditions, keep continuing to fall in deaf ears.
While those who have caused much more important damage, and the culprits of irreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at the least, await in their own home the end of the procedure. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the bidding war: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
The researchers in neurology and economy of the University of New York managed to update the neural and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be outbid in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, which is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These studies have tried to set a neural pattern of this kind of "game" with the help of auctions experiments.
One of the groups of volunteers was playing lotto, while the other group was taking part in a playful auction, during which, with the aid of a process of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), researchers were analyzing the active brain areas of the experiment's subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction whose a key element is higher bid by a third person, all the elements situated under the brainstem, called striatum, were intensively moving at the loss of the day.
This part of the brain, in addition to having several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researcher, the rise in prices is explained by the leak before the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers have pursued analyses of financial supervision.
During these, three groups were outbidding facing a partner, in various circumstances.
They have simply informed the control group of the real value of the product in question, and they have thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if they came out winners of the game too, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the same $15 from him before the auction, the members of the group also lost this money if they lost the bid.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was put with one on victory, while with the other, on failure.
By demonstrating the assumption of neurologues, members of the "against failure" players team were willing to higher bets than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be proven by any economic theory that already exists.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena noticed during auctions by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only the neural imaging methods have helped remove the contradiction between the two theories, leading on a third explanation. "- found Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when do we have to see a doctor?
In the world, around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that 100 thousand patients are carriers of the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are treated. This is due to the fact that often patients do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogenic agents and the diseases caused differ from one another.
The hepatitis viruses, in the manner of pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and the other viruses through blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
For travelers, it is anyway recommended to be vaccinated against the A and B virus. There is no vaccine against the C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated food, in most cases, accompanied by a poor  general condition, weakness, upset stomach and nausea.
Then there develops on the skin and white of the eye a visible yellowing, the faeces become lighter in colour and the urine, darker.  Recovery could take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, every year, a million people die of the most serious form of this disease, as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that according to estimates, only one patient out of ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know if they are infected by the virus, because the  pathogenic gene silently destroys the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Consequently, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who have tattoos.
Currently, we figure 200 million patients suffering from a chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine check in a laboratory, it is advised to consult one's attending physician from the note of unknown origin symptoms.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is averted.
On 30 September is the world day of hepatitis, organised for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representative of patients from around the world.
His aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, on the causes of its development and on the importance of an early illness diagnosis.
Does someone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious beliefs funtion as a kind of analgesia, which would have already made the deaths of the Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper "Telegraph" published an article stating that researchers at Oxford University have had an interesting experience while analyzing at what level the belief in God could influence tolerance to pain in human beings.
In this rather weird experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists have been subjected to electroshocks, while each one of them was looking at a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the faithful Catholics have been able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of the human brain examination, we were also able to discover that Catholics had been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating the pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, to which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians take part from different departments of the university.
Specifically, the experience is as follows: an instrument that emits sparks and broadcasts the electroshocks is set on the left hand of the experimental subject.
Researchers asked the participants in the experiment to keep looking for a long time at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th Century and the other, the Lady in Ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th Century.
Researchers who initiated this experience hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary tells a sort of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was on its calming effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scan, and during this time, received 20 electrochocs in four consecutive parts, while either watching a painting on a religious theme or the one with a more general theme.
Catholics have said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe", like someone who is "taken care of" and they "calmed down, and peace invaded them."
At the sight of the religious-themed painting, they have reported 12% less pain than when they watched the work of Leonard.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the experience himself, believes we can achieve the same effects for atheists with some other sort of powerful image, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find a picture toward which they respond very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, has welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of the faith should change and in many cases, changes effectively our personality," added Wright.
After these excellent results, all that remains is the question of the effect on the pain regulation of the subjects if believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by another painter of the same caliber?
