The Warsaw Stock Exchange made a proposal for the purchase of the Prague Stock Exchange
The stock exchange of Warsaw has proposed two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech kronor, for the purchase of 100% of the package of shares of the stock exchange of Prague.
Ludwik Sobolewski, president of the Warsaw stock market, confirmed this proposal that the Poles have made, despite the fact that the Czechs had previously excluded the Warsaw stock market from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague stock market.
The cause of this exclusion is that Warsaw's stock market is owned by the government.
99% of the shares are owned by the Polish State which wants to part from more than 60% of its actions within a few months of activity.
According to the Czech business newspaper E15, the proposal of Poles represents the most high which was made to date for the purchase of the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the NASDAQ Transatlantic Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse made ​​an offer so far.
Koblic Petr, director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among the interested parties, the Warsaw stock market would be the the least good new owner , and has not ruled out the fact that this could lead to the disappearance of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague Stock Exchange is estimated between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns by market specialists.
On the basis of an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the papers would be sold.
The biggest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance, with about 25 percent of shares, followed by the 14.7 percent of the bank Ceská Sporitelna and Tiger Holding Four S.a.r.l. with 13.5 percent.
