Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, prices for domestic manufacturers have increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - communicates the Central Statistical Office in Hungary.
Export sale prices have increased by 1.1 per cent compared to those of July 2008, whereas they fell by 3.9 percent compared to those from a year ago.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices rose 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
The domestic manufacturing sale prices have only progressed to a lesser extent: of 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors have undergone only a small increase, on the order of 0.1 percent as compared with July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the manufacturing sector of shoes and other leather items (2.8 per cent), with the manufacture of bags and belts in first place with an increase of 4.6 percent for the month, then the production of shoes with a 2.5 percent increase for the month.
The level of higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials has led to a significant monthly increase of the price of products and raw chemicals manufacturing industry (1.6 per cent).
A deflation has resulted of it in the sectors of oil processing (1.4%), in machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing (0.9 per cent) ones, and also a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices for paper production, the activities of publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant amount of the national industrial use, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices put in place by the authorities from July 1st.
Compared over a 12 month period, taking into account domestic sales in the transformation sectors, it is the price of oil processing sector that has experienced the most significant rise (32.4 percent).
In the metal products manufacturing sector, there has been an increase in prices of 13.2 percent, while in the major area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices have gone up 11 percent.
Price cuts took place in the production of textiles and textile products (2.5 percent), and in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 percent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the price rise has fluctuated between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the whole manufacturing industry, prices have risen 10.2 percent over the last year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water have exceeded by 18,7 percent higher those of the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to sectors allocation, in August, these are the founders of profit on investments that have shown the monthly price rise the most significant (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, while those of the energy producing sectors and raw materials aimed at subsequent conversion did not change as compared to the preceding month.
In August 2008, as compared to the same month in the preceding year, we witnessed the most significant increase in the areas of energy production and raw materials destined for subsequent conversion (16.8 percent).
In the sectors of production of consumer goods, an inflation of 6.8 percent was measured, while for the profit initiating sectors, a reduction of 1.4 percent.
The sale prices for export industry, in HUF, rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they have suffered a drop of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In a month, our national means of payment is weakened by 1.7 per cent compared to the Euro, and 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to the month of August 2007, it has increased by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
