Today, began in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunity, of which France is the host, representing the current presidency of the European Union.
In her speech before the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the counsel of experts, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, because this is a violation of law which most affects Roma children, and is therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French presidency, this high level conference was opened in part by Xavier Bertrand, the French Minister of Labour and Social Affairs, and in part by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Work, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the invited people to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent legal protection representatives and European civilian agencies, in the area of equal opportunities.
According to the public relations office of the deputy Fidesz from the Populist Party, Járóka warned that in addition to the discrimination that occurs during hiring, the Roma are disappearing from the labour market primarily due to their poor qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of young Romani have no high-school qualifications, and as a consequence of a poor quality basic education, only a tiny part has the opportunity to obtain a high education degree."
Furthermore, Járóka has insisted that education as a fundamental right of human beings plays a key role when one has to assert the other fundamental rights.
Investing in early education of Roma children means strengthening the economy of the European Union countries.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, equally between the Roma and the non-roms.
Indeed, the earlier a Romani child starts school, the more it increases his chances of becoming a productive member on labour market; by the tax paid from his income and his consumption, he is involved in the government budget.
"by their membership in the European Union, the Roma must be assured of their right to a quality education, and to be protected from a poor quality, sectarian education," Lívia Járóka emphasized.
According to the deputy, a European Union collaboration geared towards a goal and an action is needed for an immediate acceleration of the process of school desegregation. For this, abiding by the anti-discrimination directives in existence and in preparation is of paramount importance.
"We need to break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment. We must give Roma children the opportunities assured by democracy, so that they can participate in the future of Europe as citizens with full rights" Járóka demanded.
On behalf of "Année Européenne pour l'Égalité des Chances" guaranteed for all, the summit's aim for equality in Europe held every year since the summit in Berlin last year, is to ensure a unique platform to support the measures taken in favour of equal opportunities and for the fight against discrimination, targeted at European level and within individual countries.
