Finger pointed at MP3 players, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for a protracted period using portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announce, in a statement circulated in Brussels, quoting the Scientific Committee on the unexpected and recently identified health risks in EU(Csrseri), published today.
"From this scientific report - let us read in the footnote - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, during a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than one hour per day per week, risk a permanent hearing loss."
"I am concerned by the fact that a significant number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume may unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data - the responsible Ue continues - it is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is to raise the awareness of consumers and to make public this information.
We need to check again the existing control systems, given the scientific opinion, in order to make them entirely effective and that can follow new technologies. "
Brussels has asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists - concludes Ue executives - confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examinate with the member countries and other interested parties, which measures could possibly be adopted to protect children and adolescents in a better way against exposure to noise from portable music devices and appliances.
There is already a European standard for security, which limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100db, but the concern is growing about the hearing damages that could come from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to adequately limit these data making use of solutions like reduction of levels and of the duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee pointed out that users of portable music devices who listen to music at full volume (over 89 decibels) for five hours per week are exceeding the limits currently in force as to the maximum acceptable level of noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods, are at risk of permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 to 10 million people in the A.E.
