Students victims of high rents, up to 900 Euro for a room.
The renting market for students does not know any crisis
According to the latest survey of Sunia, the tenants' union, to rent a simple room can cost a student up to 900 Euros in Milan, 700 in Florenc, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very seriously aspect to the extend that exclude whole groups of youth to study right because of the very high overall costs that origin families must support - explains the responsible of studies department of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a widespread increase process begin even for residents.
In most cases, the rental offers in addition include a series of violations: free-type contract, unregistered, without rental limits, sub-rentals.
For the Sunia, exceptional measures through the taxation review, are needed to calm prices.
Reading the investigation, in detail, we see that in Milan, for a one-bedroom in the area of Brianza, one needs around 450 Euros; for a studio, one goes from a minimum of 650 Euros (area of Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (area of Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 Euros (area of Vittoria.)
In Florence, a bed costs, on average, 350/400 euros, a room around 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the university, it costs 250 / 280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a simple room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they charge about 600 Euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a simple) for the areas close to the other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save if you distance yourself in the outlying areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a simple in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar areas.
In Naples, you need 300/400 euros for a bed. For a single size, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas of Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, it takes 250 / 350 euros, at least 350 for a singles.
In smaller towns, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a great importance in the cities economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by students from outside the community, there is an anomaly: the rent asked for foreign students is increased by 25 / 30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, cities are getting rid of the historic movie palaces.
The historic movie theatres are closing in favour of multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city , it is like a face without eyes."
The picture provided by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, well shows what happens in major Italian suburbs, but also in the countryside cities.
The marginalisation process of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of big multirooms, and the death of consomption of Mono rooms in the cities's central areas, is one of the major events which seems us to be inevitable and undisputable; moreover, it has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, it is often historic and full of memory places, "it is like one of my friend disappeared, someone we known, with whom we shared a bit of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, the film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prize at Cannes juror, and witch was telling the poetry of a provincial auditorium, and nostalgia for a way to experience cinema, maybe forever lost.
The figures provided by ANEC, the main Association of Traders, shows everything: the last five years, 316 traditional movie theaters shut down, and these are the main cities' movie houses which have paid the bill: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan and Rome, Naples, Bologna, 6, at least in less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, the Roman Emily is at the top with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by the Tuscany (44) and the Lombardy (41).
The evidence which confirms that the advent of the multiplex is indeed primarily responsible for their demise is that these are the three Italian regions that have the most new multi-theater movie houses: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and the same number in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian operation has expanded in an irrational fashion," observes Paolo Protti, president of the ANEC," it is useful to build new structures, but it is still necessary to ensure the survival of those that already exist, because when a movie theater closes in a city, the people who frequent it are not all necessarily prepared to go to the multiplex.
Without mentioning the missed deliberation of the credit for shopkeepers: the antecedent debt of the State is around 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the government does not abide by the existing laws.
To support the industry will require between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation with the signing of a agreement between City Hall and ANEC, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-room movie houses in historic city centers and on the outskirts.
Among the expected norms, there are state tax measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for parking spaces and in certain parking garages.
"It is an initiative that I am very fond of" note Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by establishing other measures.
However, it is clear that, in order to contrast the superpower of the multiplex rooms, the traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public of today is more demanding.
Traditional movie theaters defence is a concern which has always been important for me: the closure of the Bagheria's Supercinema, place of my childhood and teenage, was the spark that convinced me to make 'New Movie House Paradiso' which I thought already 10 years ago.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and every time I walk by the Rialto  or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now both closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I look the other way so as not to see the worn-down signs covered in dirt.
