When the energy is born of waves, now the big ones are engaging.
Here is an enormous source which occupies over 70% of the surface of the planet and now big global energy firms are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, here are the new renewable sources on which colossi such as Chevron have set eyes, and are now trying to lay hands.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movement of the sea has been considered for a hundred years; and in the 1970s, at the time of the first oil crisis, research was intensified.
When oil prices lowered, around 1980, the idea of exploiting the marine energy was sidelined, but now the environmentalists and the new increase of oil prices give a big rise to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) of London valued in 2007, that 15% of worldwide electricity need could be covered by systems exploiting seas swell.
That amount would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power stations.
And furthermore, there would be the currents and the tides..
Colossi to attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been the Enersis, who in 2005, has signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it didn't really seem revolutionary.
