United States: repetition is the mother of wisdom.
It has even become amusing, the hard effort with which President Barack Obama, who has a reputation for wisdom, which mimics the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, has regarded himself as quite simple.
When he eventually let his ardently awaited document leak out, it proved to be a carbon copy of the Bush scenario for Iraq from three years ago.
Not content with using the expression "as in Iraq" several times in the same text, he has in addition not hesitated to use the title of the Bush speech in January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A New Way Forward."
Meanwhile, he has personally criticised Bush's idea to send new reinforcements in Iraq consumed by the civil war as "irresponsible and a decision with disastrous consequences."
The following months have nevertheless shown that Bush's strategy, which came from the recommendations of his campaign managers, was the only one which was possible and likely to succeed, so much so that newspapers today do not speak of Iraq at all.
This has not improved the reputation of Bush, however, objectively speaking, he left his successor a far more favourable final situation than one could have hoped.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was once again the commanding generals who asked him for a troop increase, notably the commander of the operation in Afghanistan, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite his customary subordination..
He asked for 40,000 men to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but though he lacked for a better option, he had at least cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He has managed to obtain the promise of additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he was expecting 10,000 initially.
Which leads to most of the problems in the whole Obama strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan 18 months from now and to finish the entire process three years from now. The whole Obama doctrine leads to more questions than it provides answers for.
Many have doubts about the fact that an increase of half will bring the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well organised and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out for the exact opposite - one cannot rely on anyone and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, used to change of leader day to day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing more than window dressing behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will continue to proliferate.
It is particularly difficult to balance the interests of various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity about the reports, which are further complicated by the influence of Pakistan and Iran.
Even the foundation of a "quick to act state", which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The timing of Obama's strategy is perplexing given his determination.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only got worse and it is currently on the edge of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of the reality can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent to the tumult of the war in order to their "speedy return home " will bring a miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for withdrawal of the troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it as the indirect admission of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit demonstrated that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is decreasing.
European politicians neither know nor want to explain their electorate how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor which is capable of radically altering the situation is the development of the events linked to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not have any effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves facing the very difficult question of resolving the problem by the use of military force.
It must be answered for example when, according to Obama, America will victoriously withdraw troops from Afghanistan.
Each solution of this kind will, however, drive a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only solution for Obama is the fact that three years are remaining until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to develop a new strategy in case this one would be revealed to be a flop.
