Czech discovery: a substance that works on "resistant" HIV viruses too.
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that could slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on the viruses that have already developed an immunity to medicines.
This reality has, in some cases, the upper hand based on the fact that the combination does not act as intensively against the common variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to recover from AIDS at the moment.
Nevertheless, we can extend radically the lives of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of HIV in the body.
Their consumption leads, however, to a number of side effects.
Plus, the repression of this increase brings about the development of so-called virus strain on which drugs do not have any effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a method to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are a composite of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination is blocking the virus development in a different way than all the medicines used to date and therefore they could overcome the resistance problem.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances on the basis of their knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their routes on the proteins of the virus.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are shaped by the boron atoms, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, cobalt in this case.
A sneaky and resistant virus.
The protease of the HIV is a protein of the HIV virus which is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease the mature infectious particles of the virus would not develop.
If you stop the HIV protease, you will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain the researchers in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the  Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the scientific publication Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a number of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic link, which is then systematically altered.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficiency of this series of substances on the proteases of the HIV has been tested in test tubes as well as on its resistant variations, obtained from patients infected with HIV.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarboranes is not as strong as clinical medicine, however it does not weakeon on resistannt versions against which current medicines are often ineffective.
The metalocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties, such as their biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of additional chemical modifications, are therefore interesting compounds to study further in order to move towards the development of effective medicines against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, director of the Laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of organic chemistry and biochemistry and at the Institute of molecular genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
