According to the new schedules of the CD, there will be fewer trains for the same charges.
The Czech railways will eliminate or reduce from 13 December some less loaded regional or express trains and on the contrary will increase some others.
The total cover of transport will drop at the day of coming into effect of the new schedules of two pourcent compared to today.
Most of the pricing will not change, including the base tariffs and the reduced tariff.
For example the inhabitants of the region of Ostrava will have more connections to the capital, the railways are going to add a set of pendolino trains.
Instead, an express will stop serving Bratislava.
There will be also less fast trains on the Prague - Písek - České Budějovice line, the Prague - Letohrad direct line will be drastically reduced.
At the regional level, the largest decrease in shipments concerns the region of Hradec Králové, eight per cent in total, while Prague and its environs can be pleased about an increase.
Two night trains on the Prague - Tábor - České Budějovice line have also been cancelled and the runs of some express trains on the Prague - Písek - České Budějovice line will be reduced to only a few days a week.
Among the major changes, one can see the introduction of a new direct line from Milovice to Prague: for the time being the inhabitants of Milovice must change at Lysá nad Labem.
It is the fifteenth line of the Esko suburban system, whose opening is possible thanks to the completion of the electrification of the line between Lysá and Labem and Milovice.
The long distance rails near the capital will have their final destination at the central station in Prague (Praha Hlavní Nádraží).
The ČD will introduce more SC Pendolino lines between Prague and Ostrava and trains to Šumperk/Jeseník will leave at two-hour intervals.
Travellers will no longer be able to take the Pendolino up to Bratislava from the 13th of December.
The bill this year for regional railways: 200 million kroner more.
Express trains are ordered and paid by the Ministry of Transport which will pay the railways next year a total amount of four billion crowns to settle the visible losses, the same amount as this year. The regional trains are ordered by the regions which will pay for them by a total of eight billion next year, knowing that the government will account for almost three billion.
This year regional trains are 200 millions more expensive.
The railways have newly signed a contract for ten years, until now the duration was always of one year.
The railways like the system, which also explains why they have not resorted to an increase in the prices of the vast majority of tickets.
The changes will affect only ČD Net day tickets and reduced price eLiška Internet tickets.
For passengers without a reduction card, the price of ČD Net will increase from 450 to 600 kroner.
The price of eLiška will now depend on the journey taken, while before that it was valid between the cities of a chosen region and had a single rate of 160 kroner.
