The vaccination against the pneumococcal will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococcus overturn old habits as soon as January
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
People are already speaking up, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococcal are culminating.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already defines the maximum price for vaccines that health insurance will pay for.
Specialists are also quite clear about the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children born in August.
Since January, children born last year starting August 2 can be vaccinated for free against pneumococcus.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started having the vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of the vaccine must be administered between the third and fifth month of the child's life.
Last year already one family out of four has voluntarily vaccinated its children against pneumococcus.
Yet parents paid 1,600 kroner, or more for a dose.
The vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year health insurance companies spend 300 to 450 thousand kronor on doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that non-vaccinated children would need.
Until now the State was spending about 500,000 kronor a year for all the vaccination of children.
The refunded vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package."
Pneumococcus is the cause of inflammations of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammations of meninges and blood poisonings.
According to investigations in hospitals, up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years were caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination refunded.
Will vaccination compulsory?
There are opinions regarding a possible mandatory vaccination in the future.
From January on, it must be paid by the insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His Association promotes since long vaccination against the pneumococcus.
During an international conference in which our association took part, experts have not been really happy that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think it is a direction that we now need to follow, said Kalovský.
But the health ministry does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococcus.
We are definitely not thinking in terms of the present time, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, claim doctors.
Hana cabrnochová, president of the Specialized company of pediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccine based on voluntary participation has its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a decrease of vaccination renewals. "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum, I understand the decision making the vaccination optional" said however Cabrnochová.
Experts estimate that starting next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their babies.
The vaccination against pneumococcus marks a break because it is the first children vaccination, which is funded by insurances and not by the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should free up funds for the prevention, they would therefore economize on any future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves
This is, however, linked to the concerns of paediatrician practitioners, which relates to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to buy vaccines through insurance, the doctors receiving the same manner as other vaccine products provided by the state
However some deputies feared that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct the sums from health insurance."
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurances to repay them.
According to estimates, paediatricians will have to invest individually nearly 40,000 kroner per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
That will be far from being easy, according to Cabrnochová.
