In an aging China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters preaching to them, "Mother Earth is too tired to welcome more children" and "Another baby is another grave."
They have so far learned the lesson that the authorities of Shanghai government, alarmed by the low birth rate in their city and the population ageing, have radically changed direction this summer and have begun to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instantaneous and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and all our energy to one child.
We have no second left, said Wang, 31 years old, director of human resources and father of an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of one-child policy in China, creating two generations of unique children notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, nicknamed the "Little Emperors', a population crisis is threatening the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate is 1.8 children per couple less than six when the policy was implemented.
As for the distribution of the population, it is envisaged that the number of residents greater than 60 years will explode from 16.7 percent of the population by 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050. This figure is well above the global average of around 20 percent.
That imbalance is even worse in the coastal rich cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission said that fertile couples should have babies to "help to reduce the proportion of the aging population and prevent a lack of labor in the future."
Shanghai is about to become "as old - but not as rich, however - as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual reduction
Written in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is to this day undoubtedly the most controversial requirement introduced by the communist government.
Couples who transgress this policy may have to pay huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and to suffer discrimination at the workplace.
The Chinese authorities missioned the police to help the country to avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while lawyers for human rights have denounced the abuse in implementing this policy.
In rural areas, law-enforcement representatives forced women pregnant with their second child to have an abortion.
Moreover, many couples have resorted to selective abortions, leading to an abnormally high boys-girls ratio.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which a man and a woman already have only one child -- and in 2007, they toned down their harsh slogans quite a bit.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Beijing University, said that central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time at all, the posters urging families to have only one child have been replaced with copies of the regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to request authorization.
The city government dispatched family planning authorities and volunteers to meet with couples in their homes, and to slide brochures under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of Family Planning, the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing answer
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child following the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The town of Huinan, with a population of 115,000 inhabitants, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Disappointed officials in Shanghai say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only around 165 thousand -- slightly higher than 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, the person in charge of the committee of family planning in the municipality of Caolu in Shanghai, said that the financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife Liu Juanjuan, 26, have said that they would really love to have two children and that they are legally authorized to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners wrongly consider that the one-child policy is a problem of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the first child of the couple.
It's true, they are robbing us of the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It is the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, chief human resources, said she wanted an only child because she was one herself. "We were the centre of the family and were used that everyone was looking after us."
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others."
Chen zijian, 42 years and owner of a society of translating said it more bluntly.
For couples where both are working, middle class, who are lowering the birth rate, he says, one must be selfish to succeed well.
People between 20 and 30 years old have grown up watching their parents fight during the rise of capitalism in China and they do not want to live the same way, he is quoted as saying.
Even one child asks a lot of time to his parents, he says.
A mother must abandon at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the problems of space -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "when your child is only 9 months old, you must write his CV to obtain a place in the best nursery school."
Most of his friends are ready for that experience once, said Chen, but not twice.
Our generation is the first one to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We do not want too many sacrifices.
The UN group plans projects for emissions reducing
The climate conference, sponsored by the UN - characterised so far by disorganised posturing and mutual recriminations -- is back in the spotlight on Friday, because of the publication of a document outlining the ambitious cuts in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near future.
The text which could provide the foundations of a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has emphasized the remaining barriers, as much as it has lighted up the path to take.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations which don't have much time left, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Written by a special working group from ONU, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to cope with climate change, on short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the rise in global temperature that those responsible would be prepared to tolerate.
It gives a great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Washington Representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page text about the negotiations to concentrate on what the Executive Secretary of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, said was "the full picture" regarding climate change.
It shows the guidelines of a potential agreement in which the industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, by 25 to 45 percent compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries, during the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also revied negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries to adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and droughts or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal squabbling occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the representative of the United States in the climate negotiations rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, as compared to the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, where the latter were not being funded by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming more tough toward China than the Bush administration has been two years ago.
The United States is not going to sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern who also regretted that the text is not insistent enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern has made his comments one hour after the Chinese foreign affairs deputy, He Yafei had said that the principal US negotiator, either lacked "common sense", or was "highly irresponsible" for having said earlier that week that the US would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the main world powers at stake, some flaws appeared both within the Third World and between the industrial world and the Emerging Economies.
The battle now is more relevant to the rescue of individual economies than that of saving the planet, with China and the United States cutting back on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries are ignoring scientific needs to act more boldly.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the big emitters accountable for their actions.
This is really a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, which is also adviser on the climate for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some countries which are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty, in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that negotiations will lead, at the least, to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States that includes 43 states, has drafted a 24-pages treaty proposal, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, director of the climate division of the European Commission, has said that the action of the small island states has "put political pressure on the whole political process, in part because they are now unified and are asking the emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
The debates have become an urgent matter, while the delegates were focussing on the fact that they had to solve most of the issues pending before the heads of governments come to an agreement.
High level officials such as Indian Environment Minister, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese deputy minister descended from their plane and ran into the Bella Center building to attend meetings behind closed doors and information conferences, in order to make complaints which will be considered in the course of the following week.
The real picture of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people come in and out of the Palais des Congrès every day -- activist guitar players performing nightly shows, mocking the countries which, according to them, betray each other and whose proposals are made and distributed on paper rather than by emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than on Wednesday, 60 heads of governments will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big boys playground, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice-president of Conservation International worldwide politics.
The trucks are arriving.
